window.BOOK7_COURSE=[
null,
{
 n:1,
 title:'Biology: High-Yield Compression',
 subtitle:'Part II of IX',
 tag:'Biology Review',
 foundational:'cell biology, genetics, evolution, physiology, molecular biology',
 buildsOn:null,
 setsUp:'Part III (Gen Chem Review)',
 objectives:['Distinguish prokaryotic from eukaryotic cells and name the organelle by function and distinguishing feature.','Apply Mendelian inheritance patterns, Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, and molecular genetics concepts to passage questions.','Trace the path of signals through the major organ systems: cardiovascular, respiratory, renal, endocrine, and neural.','Identify the correct division type (mitosis vs. meiosis I vs. meiosis II) from chromosome behavior alone.','Classify immune responses by cell type, antigen presentation pathway, and antibody isotype.','Predict the direction of the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve shift and its physiological consequence.'],
 opener:'Biology on the MCAT is not a single discipline but a compressed stack: molecular mechanisms underlie cell behavior, cell behavior underlies organ physiology, and organ physiology integrates across systems. This chapter moves fast through that stack. Each section tables the discriminators that separate right answers from distractors. Master the mechanisms and the clinical bridges follow automatically.',
 pinnedDisc:{label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'MHC I is on all nucleated cells and presents endogenous (intracellular) peptides to CD8 T cells. MHC II is on antigen-presenting cells only and presents exogenous peptides to CD4 T cells. Get the pairing wrong and every immune question breaks.'},
 sections:[{id:'1.1',num:'1.1',title:'1.1 Cell Biology and Molecular Mechanisms',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Cell biology questions hinge on organelle function, transport mechanism, and replication fidelity. The table below is the primary reference.'},{t:'formula',x:'CELL COMPARISON\nFeature            | Prokaryote                        | Eukaryote\nNucleus            | No (nucleoid region)              | Yes (double membrane, pores)\nRibosomes          | 70S                               | 80S (cytoplasm); 70S (mito/chloroplast)\nDNA                | Circular, in nucleoid             | Linear chromosomes, histones\nCell wall          | Peptidoglycan (bacteria)          | None in animals\nOrganelles         | None membrane-bound               | Many membrane-bound\nDivision           | Binary fission                    | Mitosis/meiosis'},{t:'formula',x:'ORGANELLE FUNCTION TABLE\nOrganelle          | Function                                  | Distinguishing feature\nNucleus            | DNA storage, transcription                | Double membrane; nucleolus makes rRNA\nRough ER           | Protein synthesis for secretion/membrane  | Studded with ribosomes; continuous with nuclear envelope\nSmooth ER          | Lipid synthesis, detox, Ca2+ storage      | No ribosomes; prominent in liver and gonads\nGolgi apparatus    | Modifies, sorts, packages proteins        | Cis receives, trans ships; glycosylation site\nLysosome           | Hydrolytic digestion                      | Acidic pH (~4.5); acid hydrolases\nPeroxisome         | Fatty acid beta-oxidation (VLCFA), H2O2   | Contains catalase\nMitochondrion      | Oxidative phosphorylation, TCA, beta-ox   | Double membrane, own DNA, cristae\nRibosome           | Protein synthesis                         | 80S (euk) or 70S (prok); rRNA + protein\nCentrosome         | Microtubule organizing center             | Two centrioles at right angles (animal)\nProteasome         | Ubiquitin-tagged protein degradation      | Barrel-shaped, ATP-dependent'},{t:'list',x:['Endosymbiotic theory: mitochondria and chloroplasts have circular DNA, 70S ribosomes, double membrane, divide by binary fission.','Cytoskeleton: microfilaments (actin, 7 nm), intermediate filaments (10 nm), microtubules (tubulin, 25 nm).','Na+/K+ ATPase: 3 Na+ out, 2 K+ in per ATP; maintains resting membrane potential.','SGLT (Na+-glucose cotransport): secondary active in intestine and kidney.','GLUT transporters: facilitated diffusion; GLUT4 is insulin-responsive in muscle and adipose.']},{t:'formula',x:'MEMBRANE TRANSPORT TABLE\nType                       | Gradient        | ATP required    | Carrier\nSimple diffusion           | Down            | No              | No (small, nonpolar)\nFacilitated diffusion      | Down            | No              | Yes (channel or carrier)\nPrimary active transport   | Against         | Yes (direct)    | Yes (e.g., Na+/K+ ATPase)\nSecondary active transport | Against (1 sol) | No (uses grad)  | Yes (symport or antiport)\nOsmosis                    | Down (water)    | No              | Aquaporins (facilitated)\nEndo/exocytosis            | Bulk            | Yes             | Vesicle-mediated'},{t:'formula',x:'MOLECULAR PROCESSES TABLE\nProcess                | Enzyme                              | Direction    | Template\nDNA replication        | DNA pol III (prok), delta/eps (euk) | 5\' to 3\'     | DNA\nTranscription          | RNA pol I=rRNA, II=mRNA, III=tRNA   | 5\' to 3\'     | DNA (antisense strand)\nTranslation            | Ribosome (peptidyl transferase)     | N to C term  | mRNA (5\' to 3\')\nReverse transcription  | Reverse transcriptase               | 5\' to 3\' DNA | RNA'},{t:'list',x:['DNA: double helix, antiparallel, A-T (2 H-bonds), G-C (3 H-bonds), sugar = deoxyribose.','RNA: single-stranded, U replaces T, sugar = ribose with 2\' OH.','Histones: positively charged (Lys, Arg); acetylation loosens chromatin; methylation often condenses.','Replication: semiconservative; bidirectional forks; helicase unwinds; SSB stabilizes; topoisomerase relieves supercoils.','Leading strand: continuous, 5\' to 3\' toward fork.','Lagging strand: discontinuous Okazaki fragments; primase lays RNA primer; DNA pol I removes primer; ligase seals.','Telomeres: TTAGGG repeats; telomerase extends in germ/stem/cancer cells.','mRNA processing (euk): 5\' cap (7-methylguanosine), 3\' poly-A tail, splicing removes introns.','Splicing: spliceosome (snRNPs) recognizes GU at 5\' splice site and AG at 3\'; forms lariat.','Genetic code: triplet, degenerate, nearly universal, no overlap; start = AUG (Met); stop = UAA, UAG, UGA.','Mutations: silent (same AA), missense (different AA), nonsense (premature stop), frameshift (indel not multiple of 3).']},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR: OPERONS vs EUKARYOTIC GENE REGULATION',x:'OPERONS (prokaryotes): polycistronic mRNA, regulated as one unit. Lac operon: induced by allolactose (removes lac repressor) AND glucose absent (cAMP-CAP binds). Trp operon: repressed when tryptophan abundant. EUKARYOTES: monocistronic mRNA; regulation at chromatin (histone acetylation opens, methylation often closes), transcription factor binding to enhancers/promoters, alternative splicing, mRNA stability, translation rate, post-translational modification. Operons toggle whole pathways; eukaryotic regulation is combinatorial and layered.'},{t:'formula',x:'CELL CYCLE TABLE\nPhase         | Key event\nG1            | Cell growth; R (restriction) point checkpoint\nS             | DNA replication; sister chromatids form\nG2            | Growth; G2/M checkpoint (DNA damage check)\nProphase      | Chromosomes condense; nuclear envelope breaks down; spindle forms\nMetaphase     | Chromosomes align at plate; M checkpoint\nAnaphase      | Sister chromatids separate to opposite poles\nTelophase     | Nuclear envelopes reform; chromosomes decondense\nCytokinesis   | Cleavage furrow (animals) or cell plate (plants)'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR: MITOSIS vs MEIOSIS I vs MEIOSIS II',x:'MITOSIS: sister chromatids separate; daughters are diploid clones. MEIOSIS I: homologous chromosomes separate (reductional division); chromosome number halves; crossing over in prophase I. MEIOSIS II: sister chromatids separate on haploid cells (looks like mitosis). Rule: if chromosome number halves, it is meiosis I. If chromatids separate in diploid cells, it is mitosis. If chromatids separate in haploid cells, it is meiosis II.'},{t:'list',x:['Sources of variation: crossing over (prophase I), independent assortment (metaphase I), random fertilization.','Mitosis: 1 diploid parent to 2 diploid identical daughters (somatic cells).','Meiosis: 1 diploid parent to 4 haploid genetically unique daughters (gametes).','Cancer hallmarks: sustained proliferative signaling, evasion of growth suppressors, resisting cell death, replicative immortality, angiogenesis, invasion/metastasis, altered metabolism, immune evasion, genomic instability, inflammation.','Proto-oncogenes (gain-of-function = oncogene): Ras, Myc, HER2, Bcr-Abl.','Tumor suppressors (loss-of-function): p53 (the guardian), Rb, BRCA1/2, APC.','p53: activated by DNA damage; induces p21 → CDK inhibition → G1 arrest; if damage severe, triggers apoptosis.']}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A cell is observed undergoing division. Chromosome number drops by half during anaphase. This event is best described as:',choices:['A) Mitotic anaphase','B) Meiosis I anaphase','C) Meiosis II anaphase','D) Cytokinesis'],answer:1,why:'Chromosome number halves only in meiosis I, when homologous chromosomes (not sister chromatids) separate. In mitosis and meiosis II, chromatids separate and ploidy is preserved within that division step.'},{stem:'Which organelle is correctly paired with its distinguishing feature?',choices:['A) Lysosome: contains catalase; neutral pH','B) Smooth ER: studded with ribosomes; lipid synthesis','C) Peroxisome: contains catalase; VLCFA beta-oxidation','D) Golgi: cis face ships vesicles to plasma membrane'],answer:2,why:'Peroxisomes contain catalase and perform beta-oxidation of very-long-chain fatty acids plus H2O2 metabolism. Lysosomes have acid hydrolases at pH ~4.5 (not neutral). Smooth ER lacks ribosomes. The trans face (not cis) of the Golgi ships vesicles outward.'}]},{id:'1.2',num:'1.2',title:'1.2 Genetics and Evolution',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Genetics questions test pattern recognition from pedigrees and quantitative reasoning from Hardy-Weinberg. Evolution questions test the type of selection from the shape of the phenotype distribution.'},{t:'formula',x:'INHERITANCE PATTERNS TABLE\nPattern               | Key features\nAutosomal dominant    | Affects both sexes; no skipped generations; ~50% offspring of affected\nAutosomal recessive   | Can skip generations; two carriers can have affected child\nX-linked recessive    | Mostly males affected; carrier mother to son; no male-to-male transmission\nX-linked dominant     | No male-to-male; affected fathers pass to ALL daughters\nMitochondrial         | Maternal only; ALL children of affected mother affected\nY-linked              | Father to all sons only'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD: Hardy-Weinberg',x:'Equation: p^2 + 2pq + q^2 = 1; p + q = 1. Assumptions: no mutation, no selection, no migration, random mating, large population. Workflow: if q^2 = disease frequency, then q = sqrt(disease freq), p = 1 - q, carrier frequency = 2pq. Punnett ratios: monohybrid 3:1 (dominant phenotype); dihybrid 9:3:3:1. Test cross: cross with homozygous recessive to determine unknown genotype.'},{t:'list',x:['Codominance: both alleles expressed (ABO blood type AB).','Incomplete dominance: blended phenotype (red x white = pink).','Penetrance: percent with genotype that express phenotype.','Expressivity: degree of expression in those who show the phenotype.','Pleiotropy: one gene, multiple phenotypes (sickle cell disease).','Epistasis: one gene masks expression of another.','Linkage: genes on same chromosome inherited together unless crossing over separates them.']},{t:'formula',x:'EVOLUTION: TYPES OF SELECTION\nType           | What is favored          | Distribution outcome       | Classic example\nDirectional    | One extreme              | Distribution shifts        | Peppered moth darkening\nStabilizing    | The mean                 | Distribution narrows       | Human birth weight\nDisruptive     | Both extremes            | Bimodal distribution       | Beak size in Darwins finches'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR: DIRECTIONAL vs STABILIZING vs DISRUPTIVE SELECTION',x:'DIRECTIONAL: one tail favored, distribution shifts. STABILIZING: mean favored, distribution narrows (reduces variation). DISRUPTIVE: both extremes favored, bimodal result, can drive speciation. Match the shape of the curve to the answer, not the name of the organism.'},{t:'list',x:['Natural selection: heritable variation + differential reproduction = change in allele frequency.','Fitness: reproductive success, not survival alone.','Sexual selection: mate choice or competition; can drive traits that decrease survival.','Genetic drift: random allele frequency change; strongest in small populations (founder effect, bottleneck).','Gene flow: migration changes allele frequencies.','Speciation: allopatric (geographic isolation); sympatric (same area, e.g., polyploidy in plants).','Reproductive isolation: prezygotic (temporal, behavioral, mechanical, gametic) and postzygotic (hybrid inviability, sterility).']},{t:'formula',x:'ECOLOGICAL INTERACTIONS TABLE\nInteraction    | Species A   | Species B\nMutualism      | +           | +\nCommensalism   | +           | 0\nParasitism     | +           | -\nPredation      | +           | -\nCompetition    | -           | -'},{t:'list',x:['Food web: producers (autotrophs) to primary consumers to secondary to tertiary; ~10% energy transfer per trophic level.','r-selected: many offspring, little parental care, unstable environments (insects, frogs).','K-selected: few offspring, much parental care, stable environments (mammals, large birds).','Exponential growth: dN/dt = rN.','Logistic growth: dN/dt = rN(1 - N/K).']}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A genetic disease has a frequency of 1 in 10,000. Assuming Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, what is the carrier frequency?',choices:['A) 1/100','B) 1/50','C) 1/10,000','D) 2/100'],answer:1,why:'q^2 = 1/10,000 so q = 1/100. p = 1 - 1/100 = 99/100. Carrier frequency = 2pq = 2 x (99/100) x (1/100) = approximately 2/100 = 1/50.'}]},{id:'1.3',num:'1.3',title:'1.3 Physiology: Cardiovascular and Respiratory',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Cardiovascular and respiratory questions combine anatomy (path of blood, valve sequence, conduction) with quantitative physiology (Starling forces, O2 transport, spirometry, acid-base).'},{t:'list',x:['Path of blood: RA to tricuspid to RV to pulmonary valve to pulmonary artery to lungs to pulmonary veins to LA to mitral (bicuspid) to LV to aortic valve to aorta to body to vena cava to RA.','Pulmonary artery carries deoxygenated blood; pulmonary vein carries oxygenated blood.','SA node: pacemaker (~70 bpm) to AV node (delay) to bundle of His to Purkinje fibers.','Cardiac muscle: striated, single nucleus, intercalated discs with gap junctions.','Stroke volume = EDV - ESV; CO = SV x HR; MAP = CO x TPR.','Frank-Starling: increased EDV leads to increased stretch leads to increased contraction force.']},{t:'formula',x:'ECG TABLE\nWave/Interval    | Represents\nP wave           | Atrial depolarization\nPR interval      | AV node delay\nQRS complex      | Ventricular depolarization (atrial repol hidden inside)\nST segment       | Ventricular plateau\nT wave           | Ventricular repolarization'},{t:'list',x:['Starling forces (capillary): hydrostatic pressure pushes fluid OUT; oncotic (colloid osmotic) pressure pulls fluid IN.','Net filtration favors out at arteriolar end, in at venular end; lymphatics return excess.','Edema causes: increased hydrostatic (heart failure), decreased oncotic (nephrotic syndrome, liver failure), increased permeability (inflammation), lymph blockage.','BP regulation: baroreceptors (carotid sinus, aortic arch), RAAS, ADH, ANP.','Hematocrit: ~45% (percent RBCs); plasma ~55%.']},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE: HOW BLOOD PRESSURE IS DEFENDED',x:'When BP drops: baroreceptors fire less, sympathetic tone increases (increased HR, contractility, vasoconstriction). Simultaneously, juxtaglomerular cells release renin, angiotensin I forms, ACE in lungs converts to angiotensin II (potent vasoconstrictor), angiotensin II stimulates aldosterone (Na+ and water retention) and ADH (water retention). Net: increased volume, increased TPR, increased MAP. ACE inhibitors and ARBs target this axis.'},{t:'list',x:['Path: nose to pharynx to larynx to trachea to bronchi to bronchioles to alveoli (gas exchange).','Diaphragm contracts: thoracic volume increases, pressure drops, air moves in (inspiration is active); expiration passive at rest.','Surfactant (type II pneumocytes): decreases surface tension; deficient in premature infants leads to RDS.']},{t:'formula',x:'LUNG VOLUMES TABLE\nVolume/Capacity              | Definition\nTidal volume (TV)            | Volume per normal breath (~500 mL)\nInspiratory reserve (IRV)    | Max additional inhalation above TV\nExpiratory reserve (ERV)     | Max additional exhalation below TV\nResidual volume (RV)         | Air remaining after max exhalation (not measurable by spirometry)\nVital capacity (VC)          | TV + IRV + ERV\nTotal lung capacity (TLC)    | VC + RV\nFunctional residual cap (FRC)| ERV + RV (after normal exhale)'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR: O2-HEMOGLOBIN CURVE SHIFTS',x:'Right shift (decreased affinity, releases O2 at tissues): increased CO2, decreased pH, increased temperature, increased 2,3-BPG (Bohr effect). Left shift (increased affinity, holds O2): decreased CO2, increased pH, decreased temperature, decreased 2,3-BPG, fetal Hb, CO poisoning. Fetal Hb shifts left = holds O2 = picks up from maternal blood. CO poisoning shifts left AND reduces capacity.'},{t:'list',x:['O2 carried: 98% on hemoglobin, 2% dissolved.','CO2 carried: ~70% as HCO3-, ~20% on Hb (carbamino), ~10% dissolved.','Oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve: sigmoid (cooperative binding); P50 ~27 mmHg.','Chloride shift: in RBC at tissues, HCO3- exits and Cl- enters.']}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A mountaineer at high altitude has low PO2. Which shift in the O2-Hb dissociation curve would most aid O2 delivery to tissues?',choices:['A) Left shift due to alkalosis from hyperventilation','B) Right shift due to increased 2,3-BPG over days at altitude','C) Left shift due to increased temperature','D) Right shift due to CO poisoning'],answer:1,why:'Chronic altitude exposure increases 2,3-BPG, shifting the curve right and decreasing Hb affinity for O2, facilitating O2 unloading at tissues. CO poisoning shifts left (wrong direction). Hyperventilation-induced alkalosis shifts left. Increased temperature shifts right but is not the primary chronic adaptation described.'},{stem:'Which lung volume CANNOT be measured by spirometry?',choices:['A) Tidal volume','B) Expiratory reserve volume','C) Vital capacity','D) Residual volume'],answer:3,why:'Residual volume is the air remaining after maximal exhalation. A spirometer cannot measure it because the patient cannot exhale it out. RV must be measured by body plethysmography or gas dilution methods.'}]},{id:'1.4',num:'1.4',title:'1.4 Physiology: Renal, GI, and Endocrine',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Renal physiology integrates nephron segment function with acid-base regulation. GI physiology centers on enzyme source and hormone function. Endocrine physiology tests receptor type and axis sequence.'},{t:'formula',x:'NEPHRON SEGMENT TABLE\nSegment                        | What it does\nGlomerulus                     | Filtration (size and charge selective)\nPCT                            | Bulk reabsorption: 65% Na+/H2O, all glucose/AAs, most HCO3-\nDescending loop of Henle       | Water reabsorption only (permeable to H2O, not solutes)\nAscending loop of Henle        | Solute reabsorption only (Na+/K+/2Cl- symporter); impermeable to H2O\nDCT                            | Na+/Cl- reabsorption; Ca2+ reabsorption (PTH-regulated)\nCollecting duct                | ADH-regulated water reabsorption; aldosterone-regulated Na+/K+'},{t:'list',x:['RAAS trigger: low BP, low Na+, or low renal perfusion to renin from JG cells to angiotensin I to ACE to angiotensin II to vasoconstriction + aldosterone + ADH.','ADH (vasopressin): inserts aquaporins in collecting duct; water reabsorbed; concentrated urine.','Aldosterone: increases Na+ in, increases K+ out, increases H+ out (principal cells).','ANP: opposes RAAS; released by atrial stretch; increases Na+ excretion, vasodilation.','Counter-current multiplier: loop of Henle creates medullary gradient; vasa recta preserves it.']},{t:'formula',x:'ACID-BASE TABLE\nDisorder               | Primary change  | Compensation\nMetabolic acidosis     | decreased HCO3- | Hyperventilation (decreased PCO2)\nMetabolic alkalosis    | increased HCO3- | Hypoventilation (increased PCO2)\nRespiratory acidosis   | increased PCO2  | Renal increased HCO3- reabsorption (slow)\nRespiratory alkalosis  | decreased PCO2  | Renal decreased HCO3- reabsorption (slow)'},{t:'list',x:['Anion gap = Na+ - (Cl- + HCO3-); normal ~8-12.','High anion gap acidosis (MUDPILES): Methanol, Uremia, DKA, Propylene glycol, Iron/INH, Lactic acidosis, Ethylene glycol, Salicylates.','Henderson-Hasselbalch: pH = 6.1 + log([HCO3-] / (0.03 x PCO2)).']},{t:'formula',x:'GI ENZYME TABLE\nEnzyme                    | Source                    | Substrate        | Optimal pH\nSalivary amylase          | Salivary glands           | Starch           | ~7 (neutral)\nPepsin                    | Chief cells (stomach)     | Proteins         | ~2 (acidic)\nPancreatic amylase        | Pancreas                  | Starch           | ~8 (alkaline)\nTrypsin/chymotrypsin      | Pancreas (zymogens)       | Proteins         | ~8\nLipase                    | Pancreas                  | Triglycerides    | ~8\nLactase/sucrase/maltase   | Small intestine brush     | Disaccharides    | ~7\nEnteropeptidase           | Duodenum                  | Activates trypsinogen | ~8'},{t:'list',x:['Stomach: HCl from parietal cells (proton pump); intrinsic factor (B12 absorption) also from parietal cells.','Gastrin: G cells stimulate increased HCl secretion.','Secretin: duodenum stimulates increased pancreatic HCO3- (neutralizes acid chyme).','CCK: duodenum (response to fat) stimulates bile release from gallbladder and increased pancreatic enzymes.','Absorption sites: duodenum (iron, Ca2+), jejunum (most nutrients), ileum (B12, bile salts), colon (water, electrolytes).','Bile: emulsifies fat; made in liver, stored in gallbladder, secreted into duodenum.','Liver: detox, plasma proteins, urea cycle, glucose homeostasis, bile, vitamin storage (A, D, E, K, B12).']},{t:'formula',x:'HORMONE CLASS TABLE\nClass               | Examples                              | Receptor location    | Mechanism\nPeptide             | Insulin, glucagon, GH, ADH, PTH       | Cell surface         | Second messenger (cAMP, IP3, DAG)\nSteroid             | Cortisol, aldosterone, estrogen, vit D| Cytoplasmic/nuclear  | Direct gene transcription\nAmine (catecholamine)| Epi, NE                              | Cell surface (a, b)  | cAMP (b) or IP3 (a1) or inhibit cAMP (a2)\nAmine (thyroid)     | T3, T4                                | Nuclear              | Gene transcription (acts like steroid)'},{t:'list',x:['HPA axis: hypothalamus CRH to anterior pituitary ACTH to adrenal cortex cortisol.','HPG axis: hypothalamus GnRH to anterior pituitary LH/FSH to gonads sex steroids.','HPT axis: hypothalamus TRH to anterior pituitary TSH to thyroid T3/T4.','Posterior pituitary: stores ADH and oxytocin (both made in hypothalamus).','Anterior pituitary hormones (FLAT PEG): FSH, LH, ACTH, TSH, Prolactin, Endorphins, GH.','Insulin: from beta cells, fed state, anabolic, moves glucose into cells via GLUT4 in muscle and fat.','Glucagon: from alpha cells, fasting state, catabolic, stimulates glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis.','PTH: increases Ca2+ (bone resorption, renal reabsorption, activates vit D). Calcitonin: decreases Ca2+. Vit D: increases intestinal Ca2+ absorption.']}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient with chronic vomiting presents with high pH, high HCO3-, and compensatory high PCO2. Which segment of the nephron is most directly responsible for generating the elevated HCO3-?',choices:['A) Ascending loop of Henle','B) Proximal convoluted tubule','C) Collecting duct','D) Glomerulus'],answer:1,why:'The PCT reabsorbs the bulk of filtered HCO3- (about 85-90%). In metabolic alkalosis from vomiting (loss of HCl), the kidneys compensate slowly by excreting HCO3-, but the PCT is the primary site of HCO3- reclamation and thus central to this derangement.'}]},{id:'1.5',num:'1.5',title:'1.5 Immune, Nervous System, and Microbiology',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Immunology questions test cell type, antigen presentation pathway, and antibody class. Neuroscience questions test the action potential sequence, neurotransmitter identity, and autonomic division. Microbiology questions test structural features that determine classification and mechanism.'},{t:'formula',x:'INNATE vs ADAPTIVE TABLE\nFeature        | Innate                                  | Adaptive\nSpecificity    | Pattern-based (PAMPs)                   | Antigen-specific\nMemory         | No                                      | Yes\nSpeed          | Immediate                               | Days to weeks (first exposure)\nCells          | Macrophages, neutrophils, NK, dendritic, mast, eosinophils, basophils | B cells, T cells\nMolecules      | Complement, cytokines, defensins        | Antibodies, TCR'},{t:'list',x:['T cells: mature in thymus; cell-mediated; require MHC presentation.','CD4 helper T: recognize MHC II (on APCs); coordinate response via cytokines.','CD8 cytotoxic T: recognize MHC I (on all nucleated cells); kill infected/tumor cells.','B cells: mature in bone marrow; humoral; produce antibodies; can act as APCs.','Plasma cells: antibody factories (differentiated B cells).','MHC I: on all nucleated cells; presents endogenous (viral) peptides.','MHC II: on APCs only (macrophages, dendritic cells, B cells); presents exogenous peptides.']},{t:'formula',x:'ANTIBODY ISOTYPES TABLE\nIsotype  | Role\nIgG      | Most abundant; secondary response; crosses placenta\nIgM      | First produced in primary response; pentamer; agglutination\nIgA      | Mucosal (saliva, tears, milk, GI); dimer\nIgE      | Allergy and parasites; binds mast cells and basophils\nIgD      | B-cell receptor; function less well-defined'},{t:'list',x:['Complement pathways: classical (Ab-triggered), alternative (microbial surface), lectin (mannose).','All converge on C3: C3a (anaphylatoxin) + C3b (opsonin) to MAC (C5-C9, lyses cell membrane).','Hypersensitivity: Type I = IgE/mast cells (allergy, anaphylaxis); Type II = Ab against cell surface; Type III = immune complexes; Type IV = T-cell delayed (TB skin test).']},{t:'formula',x:'NEUROTRANSMITTER TABLE\nNT                  | Source                                  | Effect\nACh                 | NMJ, parasympathetic, preganglionic symp | Muscle contraction; decreased in Alzheimer\nDopamine            | Substantia nigra, VTA                   | Movement (decreased in Parkinson); reward; increased in schizophrenia\nNorepinephrine      | Locus coeruleus, sympathetic post-gang  | Arousal, fight or flight\nSerotonin (5-HT)    | Raphe nuclei                            | Mood, appetite, sleep; decreased in depression\nGABA                | CNS interneurons                        | Main inhibitory; opens Cl- channels\nGlutamate           | CNS                                     | Main excitatory; learning (NMDA receptor)\nGlycine             | Spinal cord                             | Inhibitory in spinal cord\nEndorphins          | Pituitary, CNS                          | Pain modulation'},{t:'list',x:['Resting potential: ~-70 mV; maintained by Na+/K+ ATPase and K+ leak channels.','Action potential: depolarization (Na+ in) to repolarization (K+ out) to hyperpolarization (K+ still out) to return to rest.','All-or-none; refractory periods: absolute (no AP possible) then relative (stronger stimulus needed).','Myelin: oligodendrocytes in CNS, Schwann cells in PNS; saltatory conduction at nodes of Ranvier (faster conduction).','Synapse: AP to Ca2+ in presynaptic terminal to vesicle fusion to NT release to postsynaptic receptor.','CNS = brain + spinal cord; PNS = everything else.','Somatic: voluntary, skeletal muscle. Autonomic: involuntary, smooth/cardiac/glands.','Sympathetic (fight or flight): thoracolumbar, short pre/long post, NE (most), epi (adrenal medulla).','Parasympathetic (rest and digest): craniosacral, long pre/short post, ACh throughout.','Reflex arc: sensory neuron to spinal cord (interneuron) to motor neuron; monosynaptic = stretch reflex.']},{t:'formula',x:'MICROBIOLOGY CLASSIFICATION TABLE\nType        | Cell type    | Key structural features\nBacteria    | Prokaryote   | Gram+ (thick peptidoglycan, purple); Gram- (thin PG + outer LPS membrane, pink)\nViruses     | Not cells    | Obligate intracellular; DNA or RNA, ss or ds; enveloped or naked\nRetroviruses| Not cells    | RNA to DNA via reverse transcriptase (HIV)\nFungi       | Eukaryote    | Chitin cell wall, ergosterol membrane; yeasts (unicellular) or molds (hyphae)\nParasites   | Various      | Protozoa (Plasmodium, Giardia, Trypanosoma); helminths (worms)\nPrions      | None         | Misfolded proteins, no nucleic acid; cause CJD, mad cow disease'},{t:'list',x:['Gram positive examples: Staph, Strep, Bacillus, Clostridium, Listeria.','Gram negative examples: E. coli, Salmonella, Neisseria, Pseudomonas.','LPS (endotoxin) is the outer membrane component of Gram-negative bacteria; triggers septic shock.']},{t:'formula',x:'EMBRYOLOGY GERM LAYERS TABLE\nGerm layer  | Forms\nEctoderm    | Epidermis, hair, nails, nervous system, neural crest (PNS, melanocytes, adrenal medulla), lens, inner ear\nMesoderm    | Muscle, bone, cartilage, blood, heart, kidneys, gonads, dermis, connective tissue\nEndoderm    | Gut epithelium, liver, pancreas, lungs, thyroid, bladder lining'},{t:'list',x:['Cleavage: rapid mitosis without growth; morula to blastula (blastocyst in mammals).','Gastrulation: forms three germ layers; primitive streak in birds/mammals.','Neurulation: notochord induces ectoderm to form neural plate to neural tube (CNS) + neural crest (PNS).','Determination: cell fate fixed. Differentiation: cell expresses phenotype.','Induction: one tissue influences another\'s fate (notochord induces neural tube).','Apoptosis: programmed cell death; sculpts fingers, removes excess neurons.']}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient develops a delayed hypersensitivity reaction 48 hours after a TB skin test. The primary cell type mediating this response is:',choices:['A) IgE-sensitized mast cells','B) CD8 cytotoxic T cells recognizing MHC I','C) CD4 T cells (Type IV hypersensitivity)','D) Natural killer cells'],answer:2,why:'Type IV hypersensitivity is T-cell mediated (delayed). CD4 T cells previously sensitized to tuberculin recognize antigen presented on MHC II by local APCs and release cytokines that recruit macrophages, producing induration 48-72 hours later. Type I uses IgE/mast cells. Type II uses Ab against cell surfaces. NK cells are innate.'},{stem:'Which neurotransmitter acts as the primary inhibitory signal in the spinal cord?',choices:['A) GABA','B) Glycine','C) Glutamate','D) Serotonin'],answer:1,why:'Glycine is the main inhibitory neurotransmitter in the spinal cord (and brainstem), acting via ligand-gated Cl- channels. GABA is the main inhibitory transmitter in the brain. Glutamate is the main excitatory transmitter in the CNS. Serotonin modulates mood and appetite.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'The core of biology is mechanism: know the molecule, know the cell, know the system, and the MCAT question answers itself.',
 nextHint:'Part III continues with General Chemistry: equilibrium, acids/bases, and electrochemistry.',
},
{
 n:2,
 title:'General Chemistry: High-Yield Compression',
 subtitle:'Part III of IX',
 tag:'Gen Chem Review',
 foundational:'atomic structure, stoichiometry, thermodynamics, equilibrium, acids/bases, electrochemistry',
 buildsOn:'Part II (Biology Review)',
 setsUp:'Part IV (Organic Chemistry Review)',
 objectives:['Apply quantum numbers and electron configuration rules to predict atomic behavior.','Use stoichiometry and gas laws to solve mole-quantity and pressure-volume problems.','Predict spontaneity from delta-G, delta-H, delta-S, K, and cell potential.','Apply Le Chatelier\'s principle and equilibrium expressions including Ksp.','Use Henderson-Hasselbalch to reason about buffers and titration curves.','Distinguish galvanic from electrolytic cells and apply the Nernst equation.'],
 opener:'General chemistry on the MCAT tests pattern recognition above memorization. Most questions reduce to one of four frameworks: periodic trends driven by nuclear charge, equilibrium shifts driven by Le Chatelier, spontaneity driven by the delta-G equation, or electrochemistry driven by electron flow from anode to cathode. This chapter compresses all high-yield gen chem content into tables, discriminators, and rapid-recall lists. Work each section by first reciting the formula or trend from memory, then checking against the tables.',
 pinnedDisc:{label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Rate law order is determined EXPERIMENTALLY, not from the balanced equation coefficients. Only the mechanism (specifically the rate-determining step) determines rate law. Similarly, equilibrium K is determined by the balanced equation but is independent of mechanism or pathway.'},
 sections:[{id:'2.1',num:'2.1',title:'2.1 Atomic Structure and Periodic Trends',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Quantum numbers define every electron\'s address in an atom. The four quantum numbers (n, l, ml, ms) must be unique per electron by the Pauli exclusion principle.'},{t:'formula',x:'Quantum Numbers\n| Symbol | Name               | Meaning                  | Values              |\n|--------|--------------------|--------------------------|---------------------|\n| n      | Principal          | Shell, energy level      | 1, 2, 3, ...        |\n| l      | Azimuthal/angular  | Subshell, shape          | 0 to n-1 (s,p,d,f) |\n| ml     | Magnetic           | Orbital orientation      | -l to +l            |\n| ms     | Spin               | Spin direction           | +1/2 or -1/2        |'},{t:'list',x:['Pauli exclusion: no two electrons in an atom share all four quantum numbers.','Hund\'s rule: fill degenerate orbitals singly with parallel spins before pairing.','Aufbau: fill from lowest energy up: 1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p, 4s, 3d, 4p, 5s, 4d, 5p.','Anomalous configs: Cr = [Ar] 4s(1) 3d(5) and Cu = [Ar] 4s(1) 3d(10) (half/full d-shell stability).','Cations: remove electrons from highest n first (4s before 3d for transition metals).']},{t:'formula',x:'Periodic Trends\n| Trend              | Across period (L to R) | Down group       | Reason                                   |\n|--------------------|------------------------|------------------|------------------------------------------|\n| Atomic radius      | Decreases              | Increases        | More protons pull in (across); more shells (down) |\n| Ionization energy  | Increases              | Decreases        | Tighter hold (across); farther from nucleus (down) |\n| Electron affinity  | More negative          | Less negative    | Right side wants to gain; harder to hold down |\n| Electronegativity  | Increases              | Decreases        | F most EN; Cs/Fr least                   |\n| Metallic character | Decreases              | Increases        | Opposite of EN                           |'},{t:'list',x:['Effective nuclear charge: Zeff = Z - S (shielding). Increases across a period because S is nearly constant while Z rises.','Isoelectronic species: same electron count; smaller cation, larger anion.','IE exceptions: small drop at group 13 (lose first p electron) and group 16 (lose paired p electron).']},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Ionization energy exceptions: IE drops slightly from group 2 to group 13 (Al < Mg) because the 3p electron is higher in energy than 3s, and IE drops from group 15 to group 16 (S < P) because the paired 3p electron in S is easier to remove due to electron-electron repulsion. These are the two most tested IE anomalies.'},{t:'p',x:'Bonding type depends on electronegativity difference between atoms.'},{t:'formula',x:'Bond Types by delta-EN\n| Bond type         | Atoms                    | delta-EN     |\n|-------------------|--------------------------|--------------|\n| Nonpolar covalent | Two nonmetals, similar EN | < 0.5       |\n| Polar covalent    | Two nonmetals, diff EN   | 0.5 to 1.7  |\n| Ionic             | Metal + nonmetal         | > 1.7        |\n| Metallic          | Metal + metal            | delocalized electron sea |'},{t:'list',x:['Lewis structures: count valence electrons, draw skeleton, complete octets (H needs 2), check formal charges.','Formal charge = valence e- minus lone pair e- minus (1/2) bonding e-.','VSEPR: electron pairs repel; geometry by number of electron domains.','Geometries: linear (2), trigonal planar (3), tetrahedral (4), trigonal bipyramidal (5), octahedral (6).','Bond polarity vs molecular polarity: symmetric molecules with polar bonds can be nonpolar overall (CO2, CCl4).']},{t:'formula',x:'Intermolecular Forces\n| IMF                         | Strength                  | Found in                        |\n|-----------------------------|---------------------------|---------------------------------|\n| Ion-dipole                  | Strongest IMF             | Salt in water                   |\n| Hydrogen bond               | Strong dipole             | N-H, O-H, F-H to lone pair      |\n| Dipole-dipole               | Moderate                  | Polar molecules                 |\n| London dispersion (van der Waals) | Weakest (increases with size) | All molecules        |'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Stronger IMFs: higher boiling point, higher melting point, higher viscosity, higher surface tension, lower vapor pressure. Water\'s anomalies (high BP, ice less dense than liquid water, high heat capacity) all come from hydrogen bonding.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Which set of quantum numbers is INVALID?',choices:['A) n=2, l=1, ml=0, ms=+1/2','B) n=3, l=2, ml=-2, ms=-1/2','C) n=2, l=2, ml=0, ms=+1/2','D) n=4, l=1, ml=+1, ms=+1/2'],answer:2,why:'For n=2, l can only be 0 or 1 (l ranges from 0 to n-1). l=2 is not allowed when n=2.'},{stem:'CCl4 has four polar C-Cl bonds but zero net dipole moment. This is best explained by:',choices:['A) C-Cl bonds being nonpolar due to similar electronegativity','B) The tetrahedral geometry making the bond dipoles cancel by symmetry','C) London dispersion forces overcoming the bond polarity','D) Carbon having no lone pairs so no VSEPR distortion occurs'],answer:1,why:'Tetrahedral symmetry causes the four equal C-Cl bond dipoles to point in directions that vector-cancel to zero. Molecular polarity requires both polar bonds AND asymmetric geometry.'}]},{id:'2.2',num:'2.2',title:'2.2 Stoichiometry and Gas Laws',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Stoichiometry is dimensional analysis anchored to the mole. Gas law problems require temperature in Kelvin.'},{t:'list',x:['1 mole = 6.022 x 10^23 particles (Avogadro\'s number).','Molar mass: sum of atomic masses in g/mol.','Moles = mass / molar mass = volume x molarity (solutions) = PV/RT (gases).','Limiting reagent: the reactant that produces less product; run the stoichiometry from both reactants.','Percent yield = (actual / theoretical) x 100.','Empirical formula: simplest whole-number ratio. Molecular formula = (empirical formula) x n.','Balanced equation: same atom count on both sides; balance one element at a time.']},{t:'formula',x:'Ideal Gas Law and Derived Relations\nPV = nRT    R = 0.0821 L·atm/mol·K = 8.314 J/mol·K\nSTP: 0 C (273 K), 1 atm, 22.4 L/mol\n\nBoyle\'s law:    P1V1 = P2V2               (constant T, n)\nCharles\' law:   V1/T1 = V2/T2             (constant P, n)\nAvogadro\'s law: V1/n1 = V2/n2             (constant P, T)\nCombined:       P1V1/T1 = P2V2/T2\nDalton\'s:       P_total = sum of P_i;  P_i = X_i x P_total\nGraham\'s effusion: rate1/rate2 = sqrt(M2/M1)'},{t:'formula',x:'Real Gas Deviations\n| Condition         | Deviation from ideal                           |\n|-------------------|------------------------------------------------|\n| High pressure      | Molecules close: finite volume matters; measured V > ideal V |\n| Low temperature    | Attractions matter; measured P < ideal P        |\n| Ideal behavior     | Low P, high T, small nonpolar molecules         |\n\nvan der Waals equation: (P + a(n/V)^2)(V - nb) = nRT\n  a corrects for intermolecular attractions\n  b corrects for finite molecular volume'},{t:'list',x:['Phase diagram regions: solid (low T, high P), liquid (mid range), gas (high T, low P).','Triple point: all three phases coexist.','Critical point: above this T and P, no liquid-gas distinction (supercritical fluid).','Water: solid-liquid boundary has negative slope (ice less dense than liquid).','Sublimation: solid directly to gas (e.g., dry ice, frost evaporation on cold days).']},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Graham\'s law: lighter gas effuses FASTER. Rate is inversely proportional to the square root of molar mass. If gas A is 4x heavier than gas B, gas B effuses twice as fast (sqrt of 4 = 2). Test questions often give a ratio and ask you to identify the gas, or give two gases and ask for the ratio of effusion rates.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 2.0 L container of gas at 300 K and 1.5 atm is heated to 600 K at constant volume. What is the new pressure?',choices:['A) 0.75 atm','B) 1.5 atm','C) 3.0 atm','D) 6.0 atm'],answer:2,why:'At constant volume: P1/T1 = P2/T2. P2 = P1 x (T2/T1) = 1.5 x (600/300) = 1.5 x 2 = 3.0 atm. Temperature doubles, so pressure doubles (Gay-Lussac\'s law).'}]},{id:'2.3',num:'2.3',title:'2.3 Thermodynamics and Kinetics',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Thermodynamics predicts whether a reaction will occur (spontaneity); kinetics predicts how fast. These are independent: a spontaneous reaction can be kinetically slow (diamond to graphite).'},{t:'formula',x:'Thermodynamic Quantities\n| Quantity             | Symbol | Sign convention                                   |\n|----------------------|--------|---------------------------------------------------|\n| Enthalpy             | delta-H | (+) endothermic absorbs heat; (-) exothermic releases |\n| Entropy              | delta-S | (+) disorder increases; (-) disorder decreases    |\n| Gibbs free energy    | delta-G | (-) spontaneous; (+) nonspontaneous; (0) equilibrium |\n| Heat                 | q      | (+) into system; (-) out of system                |\n| Work                 | w      | (+) on system; (-) by system (chemistry convention) |'},{t:'formula',x:'Key Thermodynamic Equations\ndelta-G = delta-H - T(delta-S)          (Gibbs equation)\ndelta-G degrees = -RT ln K = -nFE degrees  (links delta-G, K, E)\n\nSpontaneity summary:\n  delta-H < 0, delta-S > 0: always spontaneous (delta-G always negative)\n  delta-H > 0, delta-S < 0: never spontaneous (delta-G always positive)\n  delta-H < 0, delta-S < 0: spontaneous at low T\n  delta-H > 0, delta-S > 0: spontaneous at high T\n\nLaws:\n  1st law: delta-U = q + w  (energy conserved)\n  2nd law: delta-S_universe > 0 for spontaneous process\n  3rd law: S of perfect crystal at 0 K = 0\n\nCalorimetry:\n  Constant P: q = delta-H; Constant V: q = delta-U\n  Sensible heat: q = mc(delta-T)\n  Phase change: q = mL  (constant T)\n\nHess\'s law: delta-H overall = sum of delta-H steps (enthalpy is a state function)'},{t:'p',x:'Kinetics: rate law and integrated rate laws are determined experimentally from concentration vs time data.'},{t:'formula',x:'Kinetics Equations\nRate = -delta-[reactant]/delta-t = +delta-[product]/delta-t  (divide by stoich coefficient)\nRate law: rate = k[A]^x [B]^y  (orders x,y determined experimentally)\n\nIntegrated rate laws:\n  Zero order:   [A] = [A]0 - kt;          t(1/2) depends on [A]0\n  First order:  ln[A] = ln[A]0 - kt;      t(1/2) = 0.693/k  (independent of [A]0)\n  Second order: 1/[A] = 1/[A]0 + kt;     t(1/2) = 1/(k[A]0)\n\nArrhenius: k = A * exp(-Ea/RT)\n  Higher T or lower Ea: faster rate\n\nCatalyst: lowers Ea equally for forward and reverse; does NOT change delta-G or K\nTransition state: highest-energy point on reaction coordinate; activated complex; cannot be isolated'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Rate-determining step (RDS) vs overall reaction: the rate law reflects only steps up to and including the slowest step. Fast steps before the RDS contribute via their equilibrium constants. Fast steps after the RDS do not affect the rate law. The molecularity of the elementary RDS gives the order with respect to its reactants, after substituting equilibria from earlier fast steps.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Arrhenius: higher T or lower Ea gives faster rate. A catalyst lowers Ea but does NOT change delta-G or K; it only speeds the approach to equilibrium. First-order half-life is constant regardless of starting concentration: t(1/2) = 0.693/k.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A reaction has delta-H = +30 kJ/mol and delta-S = +100 J/mol·K. At what temperature range is this reaction spontaneous?',choices:['A) Always spontaneous','B) Never spontaneous','C) Spontaneous below 300 K','D) Spontaneous above 300 K'],answer:3,why:'delta-G = delta-H - T(delta-S). With delta-H > 0 and delta-S > 0, delta-G becomes negative only when T(delta-S) > delta-H, i.e., T > 30000 J / 100 J/K = 300 K. Spontaneous above 300 K.'},{stem:'A catalyst is added to a reaction at equilibrium. Which is the best prediction?',choices:['A) The equilibrium constant K increases.','B) The equilibrium position shifts toward products.','C) The reaction reaches equilibrium faster but K is unchanged.','D) The activation energy increases for the reverse reaction only.'],answer:2,why:'A catalyst lowers Ea equally for forward and reverse reactions. It speeds the approach to equilibrium but does not change K or the equilibrium position. delta-G and K are thermodynamic quantities, not kinetic ones.'}]},{id:'2.4',num:'2.4',title:'2.4 Equilibrium',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Equilibrium is dynamic: forward and reverse rates are equal. The equilibrium expression excludes pure solids and liquids.'},{t:'formula',x:'Equilibrium Expressions\nK_eq = [products]^c / [reactants]^a   (pure solids and liquids excluded)\nKp = Kc(RT)^(delta-n)    where delta-n = moles gas products - moles gas reactants\n\nReaction quotient Q vs K:\n  Q < K: reaction proceeds forward (makes more product)\n  Q > K: reaction proceeds reverse (makes more reactant)\n  Q = K: system is at equilibrium\n\nKsp: for sparingly soluble salts\n  e.g., AgCl(s) <-> Ag+ + Cl-;  Ksp = [Ag+][Cl-]\n  Precipitate forms when Q > Ksp\n  Common ion effect: adding a common ion lowers solubility (Q > Ksp temporarily, shifts left)'},{t:'formula',x:'Le Chatelier\'s Principle: Stress and Response\n| Stress                    | Response                                    |\n|---------------------------|---------------------------------------------|\n| Add reactant              | Shift forward (toward products)             |\n| Remove product            | Shift forward (toward products)             |\n| Increase T (endothermic rxn) | Shift forward (K increases)             |\n| Increase T (exothermic rxn)  | Shift reverse (K decreases)             |\n| Increase P                | Shift toward fewer moles of gas             |\n| Add inert gas (constant V) | No shift                                   |\n| Add catalyst              | No shift; only speeds approach to equilibrium |'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Temperature is the ONLY stress that changes K. All other Le Chatelier stresses shift Q but leave K unchanged; the system shifts to restore Q = K. Adding an inert gas at constant volume does not change partial pressures of reactants or products, so no shift occurs. Adding an inert gas at constant total pressure does dilute all gases and can cause a shift toward more moles of gas.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Ksp and common ion: adding NaCl to a saturated AgCl solution increases [Cl-] and drives the dissolution equilibrium left, precipitating more AgCl. The molar solubility of AgCl is lower in 0.1 M NaCl than in pure water.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'For the reaction N2(g) + 3H2(g) <-> 2NH3(g), what happens to K when temperature is increased (the reaction is exothermic)?',choices:['A) K increases because higher T always favors the forward reaction.','B) K decreases because heat is a product and adding stress shifts the reaction left.','C) K is unchanged because it is only affected by concentration, not temperature.','D) K increases because the rate constant k increases with temperature.'],answer:1,why:'For an exothermic reaction, heat is a product. Increasing T is equivalent to adding a product, shifting equilibrium left, meaning less NH3 at equilibrium. Therefore K decreases. K is temperature-dependent; only temperature changes K.'}]},{id:'2.5',num:'2.5',title:'2.5 Acids, Bases, and Buffers',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Three acid-base frameworks appear on the MCAT. Lewis is broadest (includes non-proton transfers); Bronsted-Lowry is most tested; Arrhenius is the most limited.'},{t:'formula',x:'Acid-Base Definitions\n| Framework      | Acid                        | Base                        |\n|----------------|-----------------------------|-----------------------------| n| Arrhenius       | Releases H+ in water        | Releases OH- in water       |\n| Bronsted-Lowry  | Proton donor                | Proton acceptor             |\n| Lewis           | Electron pair acceptor      | Electron pair donor         |'},{t:'list',x:['pH = -log[H+]; pOH = -log[OH-]; pH + pOH = 14 at 25 C.','Kw = [H+][OH-] = 1 x 10^-14 at 25 C.','Strong acids (fully dissociate): HCl, HBr, HI, HNO3, H2SO4, HClO4, HClO3.','Strong bases: group 1 hydroxides (LiOH, NaOH, KOH, RbOH, CsOH), Ca(OH)2, Sr(OH)2, Ba(OH)2.','Conjugate pair: differ by one H+. Stronger acid gives weaker conjugate base.','Ka x Kb = Kw for a conjugate pair; pKa + pKb = 14.']},{t:'formula',x:'Henderson-Hasselbalch and Buffer Rules\npH = pKa + log([A-]/[HA])\n\nBuffer: weak acid + its conjugate base (or weak base + its conjugate acid)\n  Best buffering: pH within +/- 1 of pKa\n  At half-equivalence point: [A-] = [HA], so pH = pKa\n\nTitration landmarks:\n  Strong acid + strong base: equivalence at pH 7\n  Weak acid + strong base:   equivalence at pH > 7; half-equivalence at pH = pKa\n  Indicators: change color near their own pKa'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'At the half-equivalence point of a weak acid titration, exactly half the acid has been neutralized, so [HA] = [A-] and pH = pKa directly from Henderson-Hasselbalch. At the equivalence point, all acid is converted to conjugate base, which hydrolyzes to give a basic solution (pH > 7). These two points are the most tested on MCAT titration curve questions.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD: Acid-Base in the Body',x:'Blood pH is held at 7.35-7.45 by the bicarbonate buffer (HCO3- / H2CO3 / CO2). Lungs regulate CO2 (fast, minutes); kidneys regulate HCO3- (slow, hours to days). Hyperventilation blows off CO2, raising pH: respiratory alkalosis. Diabetic ketoacidosis produces ketoacids: metabolic acidosis with elevated anion gap, compensated by hyperventilation (Kussmaul breathing). Henderson-Hasselbalch for blood: pH = 6.1 + log([HCO3-] / 0.03 x PCO2).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A buffer is made with acetic acid (pKa = 4.74) and sodium acetate. The ratio [acetate]/[acetic acid] = 10. What is the pH?',choices:['A) 3.74','B) 4.74','C) 5.74','D) 6.74'],answer:2,why:'Henderson-Hasselbalch: pH = pKa + log([A-]/[HA]) = 4.74 + log(10) = 4.74 + 1 = 5.74. When the base/acid ratio is 10:1, pH is one unit above pKa.'},{stem:'A weak acid (pKa = 5.0) is titrated with NaOH. At the equivalence point, what is true of the solution?',choices:['A) pH = 7.0 because the acid and base have fully neutralized each other.','B) pH < 7 because residual weak acid remains.','C) pH > 7 because the conjugate base hydrolyzes to produce OH-.','D) pH = pKa = 5.0 because half the acid is converted.'],answer:2,why:'At the equivalence point, all weak acid is converted to its conjugate base (A-). The conjugate base is a weak base that undergoes hydrolysis: A- + H2O <-> HA + OH-, producing a basic solution with pH > 7. pH = 7 only for strong acid-strong base titrations.'}]},{id:'2.6',num:'2.6',title:'2.6 Electrochemistry',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Electrochemistry integrates thermodynamics (delta-G), equilibrium (K), and redox chemistry. The mnemonic OIL RIG (Oxidation Is Loss, Reduction Is Gain) anchors all cell reasoning.'},{t:'list',x:['Oxidation: loss of electrons (OIL). Reduction: gain of electrons (RIG).','Oxidizing agent gets reduced; reducing agent gets oxidized.','Oxidation state rules: H = +1 (except metal hydrides: -1); O = -2 (except peroxides: -1).','Anode = oxidation; cathode = reduction. Mnemonic: Anode-oxidation (both start with vowels).','Electrons flow from anode to cathode through the external wire (both galvanic and electrolytic cells).','Salt bridge (galvanic cell): maintains charge balance; cations migrate to cathode compartment, anions to anode.']},{t:'formula',x:'Galvanic vs Electrolytic Cell Comparison\n| Feature             | Galvanic (Voltaic)           | Electrolytic                  |\n|---------------------|------------------------------|-------------------------------|\n| Spontaneity         | Spontaneous, delta-G < 0     | Nonspontaneous, delta-G > 0   |\n| E degrees cell      | E degrees > 0                | E degrees < 0                 |\n| Energy              | Generates electricity        | Requires external electricity |\n| Anode polarity      | Negative terminal            | Positive terminal             |\n| Cathode polarity    | Positive terminal            | Negative terminal             |\n| Oxidation at anode  | Yes                          | Yes                           |\n| Reduction at cathode | Yes                         | Yes                           |'},{t:'formula',x:'Key Electrochemistry Equations\nE degrees_cell = E degrees_cathode - E degrees_anode  (both as reduction potentials)\ndelta-G degrees = -nFE degrees_cell     F = 96485 C/mol\ndelta-G degrees = -RT ln K = -nFE degrees\n\nNernst equation:\n  E = E degrees - (RT/nF) ln Q\n  E = E degrees - (0.0592/n) log Q  (at 25 C)\n  At equilibrium: E = 0, Q = K\n\nFaraday\'s laws:\n  moles e- = I x t / F    (I = current in amperes, t = time in seconds)\n  mass deposited is proportional to charge passed'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Galvanic vs electrolytic cell sign confusion: BOTH cell types have anode = oxidation and cathode = reduction, and electrons flow anode to cathode in the external wire. The difference is the POLARITY of the terminals. In a galvanic cell, the anode is negative (electrons leave it spontaneously). In an electrolytic cell, the anode is connected to the positive terminal of the external battery (electrons are forced out). The oxidation-at-anode rule holds for both; only the terminal labels flip.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'The three-way link: delta-G degrees = -RT ln K = -nFE degrees. Know the sign conventions: positive E degrees means spontaneous (delta-G < 0, K > 1). Nernst equation: as Q increases, E decreases; when Q = K, E = 0 (battery dead). Concentration cells: same electrode material but different ion concentrations; the cell runs until concentrations equalize.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A galvanic cell has E degrees_cathode = +0.34 V and E degrees_anode = -0.76 V (both as reduction potentials). What is E degrees_cell?',choices:['A) -0.42 V','B) +0.42 V','C) +1.10 V','D) -1.10 V'],answer:2,why:'E degrees_cell = E degrees_cathode - E degrees_anode = +0.34 - (-0.76) = +0.34 + 0.76 = +1.10 V. A positive E degrees confirms the cell is galvanic and spontaneous (delta-G < 0).'},{stem:'In an electrolytic cell, the direction of electron flow in the external circuit is:',choices:['A) From cathode to anode.','B) From anode to cathode.','C) Alternating, driven by the AC power supply.','D) From the positive terminal of the battery to the cathode.'],answer:1,why:'In all electrochemical cells (galvanic and electrolytic), electrons flow from anode to cathode in the external wire. The external power supply in an electrolytic cell forces this non-spontaneous electron flow by making the anode positive and the cathode negative.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Gen chem is patterns: periodic trends driven by nuclear charge, equilibrium shifts from Le Chatelier, spontaneity from the delta-G equation, and electron movement from anode to cathode.',
 nextHint:'Part IV continues with Organic Chemistry: reactions, mechanisms, and spectroscopy.',
},
{
 n:3,
 title:'Organic Chemistry: High-Yield Compression',
 subtitle:'Part IV of IX',
 tag:'Orgo Review',
 foundational:'functional groups, stereochemistry, substitution/elimination, carbonyl reactions, spectroscopy',
 buildsOn:'Part III (Gen Chem Review)',
 setsUp:'Part V (Physics Review)',
 objectives:['Assign R/S and E/Z configurations and distinguish enantiomers from diastereomers.','Predict SN1, SN2, E1, or E2 pathway from substrate class, nucleophile/base strength, and solvent.','Rank carbonyl derivative reactivity and predict nucleophilic addition or acyl substitution products.','Read IR, 1H NMR, and MS data to identify functional groups and connectivity.','Connect amino acid, carbohydrate, and lipid structures to their biological roles.'],
 opener:'Organic chemistry on the MCAT is a mechanism and pattern test, not a synthesis marathon. Every question traces back to a small set of principles: electron-pair pushing from nucleophile to electrophile, the effect of substrate geometry and solvent on reaction pathway, and the way functional groups reveal themselves in spectroscopy. This chapter compresses the high-yield material into tables and discriminators so you can drill patterns rather than memorize isolated reactions. Aromatic chemistry, stereochemistry, carbonyl reactivity, and biological molecules are the four pillars tested most heavily; SN1/SN2/E1/E2 is the single most-tested mechanism block.',
 pinnedDisc:{label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'SN2 requires a strong nucleophile, polar aprotic solvent, and a primary (or methyl) substrate. SN1 requires only a polar protic solvent and a tertiary (or secondary) substrate because the key step is unimolecular carbocation formation. Switching from polar aprotic to polar protic shifts the outcome from SN2 toward SN1/E1.'},
 sections:[{id:'3.1',num:'3.1',title:'3.1 Stereochemistry',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Stereochemistry describes spatial arrangement of atoms in molecules with the same connectivity. Key terms: stereocenter (sp3 carbon with 4 different groups), chirality (nonsuperimposable mirror image), enantiomers (mirror images with all stereocenters inverted), diastereomers (stereoisomers that are NOT mirror images, at least one but not all stereocenters differ).'},{t:'formula',x:'Hybridization | Geometry | Bond angle | Bond types\nsp | Linear | 180 deg | 2 sigma + 2 pi (triple bond or two doubles)\nsp2 | Trigonal planar | 120 deg | 3 sigma + 1 pi (double bond)\nsp3 | Tetrahedral | 109.5 deg | 4 sigma only'},{t:'list',x:['Sigma bond: head-on overlap; present in all bonds; rotation allowed.','Pi bond: side-on overlap; only in double or triple bonds; prevents rotation.','Chirality: nonsuperimposable mirror image; usually has a stereocenter.','Meso compound: has stereocenters but an internal mirror plane; achiral overall.','Max stereoisomers: 2^n where n = number of stereocenters.','R/S assignment (CIP): rank substituents by atomic number; place lowest priority away from viewer; clockwise = R, counterclockwise = S.','E/Z assignment: higher priority groups on same side = Z; opposite sides = E.','Enantiomers: identical physical properties except optical rotation (opposite sign) and behavior in chiral environments (receptor binding, chiral chromatography).','Diastereomers: different melting points, boiling points, solubility, and chromatographic retention times.','Cis/trans isomers are a special case of diastereomers.']},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'ENANTIOMERS vs DIASTEREOMERS: Enantiomers are mirror images with ALL stereocenters inverted; they share every physical property except optical rotation direction and chiral-environment interactions. Diastereomers are NOT mirror images; at least one but not all stereocenters differ; they have different melting points, boiling points, solubility, and retention times. Cis/trans isomers on a ring or double bond are diastereomers.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Aromaticity (Huckel rule): cyclic + planar + fully conjugated + 4n+2 pi electrons (n = 0,1,2,...). Antiaromatic: 4n pi electrons, very unstable. Conjugation (alternating single/double bonds) allows delocalization and lowers energy. Resonance structures contribute to a weighted average; the most stable contributor dominates.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'2-bromobutane treated with sodium hydroxide gives mostly inversion product with no carbocation rearrangement. Which mechanism is operating?',choices:['A) SN1','B) SN2','C) E1','D) E2'],answer:1,why:'NaOH is a strong nucleophile. A secondary substrate with strong nucleophile and polar aprotic conditions gives SN2, which proceeds with backside attack (Walden inversion) and no carbocation intermediate.'},{stem:'Which pair of compounds are diastereomers?',choices:['A) (R)-lactic acid and (S)-lactic acid','B) (2R,3R)-tartaric acid and (2S,3S)-tartaric acid','C) (2R,3S)-tartaric acid and (2S,3R)-tartaric acid','D) (2R,3R)-tartaric acid and (2R,3S)-tartaric acid'],answer:3,why:'Diastereomers differ at some but not all stereocenters. (2R,3R) vs (2R,3S) share C2 configuration but differ at C3, making them diastereomers (not mirror images).'}]},{id:'3.2',num:'3.2',title:'3.2 Substitution and Elimination',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Four competing pathways: SN1, SN2, E1, E2. The outcome depends on substrate class (primary, secondary, tertiary), nucleophile/base strength and size, solvent polarity and protic/aprotic character, and temperature. Mastering the decision tree between these four mechanisms is the single highest-yield skill in orgo for the MCAT.'},{t:'formula',x:'Factor | SN1 | SN2 | E1 | E2\nSubstrate | 3 deg > 2 deg | 1 deg > 2 deg | 3 deg > 2 deg | 3 deg > 2 deg > 1 deg\nNucleophile/base | Weak nucleophile | Strong nucleophile | Weak base | Strong, bulky base\nSolvent | Polar protic | Polar aprotic | Polar protic | Either\nKinetics | 1st order (substrate only) | 2nd order | 1st order | 2nd order\nStereochemistry | Racemization | Inversion (Walden) | No specific | Anti-periplanar required\nCarbocation intermediate | Yes (can rearrange) | No | Yes (can rearrange) | No\nFavored at higher temperature | Either | Either | Yes | Yes'},{t:'list',x:['Carbocation stability: 3 deg > 2 deg > 1 deg > methyl.','Strongest stabilizers: resonance (benzylic, allylic); then hyperconjugation and induction.','Polar protic solvents (water, alcohols) stabilize carbocations and ions; favor SN1/E1.','Polar aprotic solvents (DMSO, DMF, acetone) leave nucleophile free (naked); favor SN2.','Bulky base (LDA, KOtBu): favors E2 over SN2; gives Hofmann product (less substituted alkene).','Small base (NaOEt, NaOH): favors Zaitsev product (more substituted, more stable alkene).','E2 requires anti-periplanar geometry (H and leaving group 180 deg apart).']},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'SN1 vs SN2 decision: Is the substrate tertiary? If yes, polar protic solvent, weak nucleophile -> SN1 (racemization). If substrate is primary or secondary, strong nucleophile, polar aprotic -> SN2 (inversion). Higher temperature pushes secondary and tertiary substrates toward elimination (E1 or E2). A strong, bulky base at any temperature pushes toward E2.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'SN1/E1 share a carbocation intermediate and can show rearrangements (hydride or methyl shift). SN2 and E2 are concerted (no intermediate). Racemization = SN1. Inversion = SN2. Anti-periplanar geometry = E2.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A tertiary alkyl bromide is dissolved in ethanol/water with a small amount of sodium ethoxide. Which product(s) are expected?',choices:['A) Inversion product via SN2 only','B) Racemic mixture via SN1 and/or Zaitsev alkene via E1','C) Hofmann alkene via E2 only','D) No reaction because tertiary substrates are unreactive'],answer:1,why:'Polar protic solvent (ethanol/water) with a weak base/nucleophile (low concentration NaOEt) and a tertiary substrate favors SN1 (racemization) and E1 (Zaitsev alkene). SN2 is blocked at tertiary centers by steric hindrance.'}]},{id:'3.3',num:'3.3',title:'3.3 Carbonyl Chemistry',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Carbonyl groups (C=O) are the most reactive functional groups in orgo. The electrophilic carbonyl carbon is attacked by nucleophiles. Reactivity varies by substituent on the carbonyl: the better the leaving group on the acyl carbon, the more reactive the carbonyl derivative. Aldehydes and ketones undergo nucleophilic addition; acid derivatives undergo nucleophilic acyl substitution.'},{t:'formula',x:'Carbonyl derivative reactivity (most to least reactive):\nAcid halide (R-COCl) > Anhydride > Ester (~equal) > Carboxylic acid > Amide\nReason: leaving group stability. Cl- is best leaving group; amide N is worst (resonance donation + poor leaving group).'},{t:'formula',x:'Oxidation ladder:\n1 deg alcohol -> aldehyde -> carboxylic acid\n2 deg alcohol -> ketone\n3 deg alcohol -> no oxidation product'},{t:'list',x:['Nucleophilic addition (aldehydes/ketones): Nu attacks C=O -> tetrahedral alkoxide -> protonate to give alcohol.','Hydrate (gem-diol): water adds to carbonyl; unstable for most, except formaldehyde.','Hemiacetal: one ROH adds; unstable except cyclic form in sugars.','Acetal: two ROH or diol; stable; used as a protecting group; requires acid catalyst and dehydration.','Imine (Schiff base): primary amine + carbonyl -> lose water -> R2C=NR\'.','Enamine: secondary amine + carbonyl -> lose water -> R2C=CR\'-NR\'\'2.','Cyanohydrin: HCN adds to carbonyl -> R2C(OH)(CN).','Alpha-hydrogen acidity: pKa ~20 for ketones, ~25 for esters; due to enolate resonance stabilization.','Keto-enol tautomerism: keto form usually favored; interconverted by acid or base.','Aldol condensation: enolate attacks carbonyl carbon of another molecule -> beta-hydroxy carbonyl; can dehydrate to alpha,beta-unsaturated carbonyl.','Claisen condensation: ester enolate attacks another ester -> beta-ketoester (e.g., acetoacetate synthesis).','Decarboxylation: beta-keto acids and malonic acids lose CO2 on heating via cyclic transition state.']},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Reactivity order for carbonyl derivatives: acid halide > anhydride > ester ~ COOH > amide. Aldehydes are more reactive than ketones (less steric, less electron donation). Alpha-H on ketone (pKa 20) is more acidic than on ester (pKa 25) because the enolate is stabilized by C=O resonance on both sides in beta-diketones.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Which reagent converts an ester to a carboxylic acid most directly?',choices:['A) LDA, then H3O+','B) Aqueous acid or base hydrolysis (saponification with NaOH)','C) Primary amine','D) HCN'],answer:1,why:'Esters hydrolyze under acid or base conditions. Base hydrolysis (saponification with NaOH) is irreversible and gives the carboxylate salt, which is protonated to the carboxylic acid on workup. LDA would form the ester enolate, not hydrolyze it.'},{stem:'An aldol condensation between two molecules of acetaldehyde gives an initial product. What is the structure of that beta-hydroxy carbonyl?',choices:['A) 3-hydroxybutanal','B) 2-hydroxybutanal','C) Butanediol','D) Crotonaldehyde'],answer:0,why:'The enolate from one acetaldehyde attacks the carbonyl carbon of the second, giving 3-hydroxybutanal (beta-hydroxy group at C3, aldehyde at C1). Dehydration of this product gives crotonaldehyde (D), but that is the dehydration product, not the initial aldol adduct.'}]},{id:'3.4',num:'3.4',title:'3.4 Aromatic Chemistry and EAS',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Benzene is aromatic (cyclic, planar, fully conjugated, 6 pi electrons, satisfies 4n+2 with n=1). It resists addition reactions because those would destroy aromaticity. Instead, benzene undergoes electrophilic aromatic substitution (EAS), which regenerates the aromatic ring after electrophile attack.'},{t:'list',x:['EAS mechanism: electrophile is generated (e.g., Br+ from Br2/FeBr3) -> attacks ring pi system -> arenium ion (sigma complex, carbocation) -> deprotonation restores aromaticity.','Common EAS reactions: halogenation (Br2/FeBr3), nitration (HNO3/H2SO4), sulfonation (H2SO4/SO3), Friedel-Crafts alkylation (RCl/AlCl3), Friedel-Crafts acylation (RCOCl/AlCl3).','Friedel-Crafts alkylation limitation: multiple alkylations and carbocation rearrangements can occur. Acylation is preferred for control.','Activating groups donate electrons to ring; deactivating groups withdraw electrons.','Halogens: inductive withdrawal deactivates ring (net deactivator), but lone pair donation directs ortho/para (unique case).']},{t:'formula',x:'Substituent | Effect | Directs to\n-OH, -OR, -NH2, -NR2 | Strong activator (lone pair donation) | ortho/para\nAlkyl, -Ar | Weak activator (hyperconjugation/induction) | ortho/para\n-F, -Cl, -Br, -I | Weak deactivator BUT lone pair director | ortho/para\n-NO2, -CN, -SO3H, -COR, -COOH | Strong deactivator | meta\n-NR3+ | Strong deactivator | meta'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'ORTHO/PARA vs META DIRECTORS: Ortho/para directors stabilize the arenium ion at ortho or para positions via resonance (lone pair groups) or hyperconjugation (alkyl). Halogens are deactivators overall (inductive withdrawal) but direct ortho/para because lone pairs donate into the ring at those positions. Meta directors (-NO2, -COR, -CN) destabilize the ortho/para arenium ions more than the meta ion because placing positive charge adjacent to an electron-withdrawing group is especially unfavorable.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Aromaticity = cyclic + planar + fully conjugated + 4n+2 pi electrons. Antiaromatic = 4n pi electrons (very unstable). The arenium (Wheland) intermediate in EAS is NOT aromatic; the final step restores aromaticity by losing a proton, not by adding a nucleophile (that would keep the ring non-aromatic).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Nitration of chlorobenzene gives predominantly which product?',choices:['A) meta-nitrochlorobenzene','B) ortho- and para-nitrochlorobenzene','C) 1,2-dichlorobenzene','D) No reaction because chlorine deactivates the ring completely'],answer:1,why:'Chlorine is a halogen: it deactivates the ring by inductive withdrawal but directs ortho/para via lone pair resonance donation into the ring. Nitration still occurs (just more slowly than unsubstituted benzene) and gives ortho and para products predominantly.'}]},{id:'3.5',num:'3.5',title:'3.5 Spectroscopy',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Spectroscopy identifies functional groups (IR), connectivity and environment of protons (1H NMR), unique carbon environments (13C NMR), and molecular weight plus fragmentation (MS). On the MCAT, spectroscopy questions give you a spectrum and ask you to match it to a structure or identify a functional group.'},{t:'formula',x:'IR absorptions (cm-1) | Bond/group\n~3300 (broad) | O-H hydrogen-bonded (alcohol, carboxylic acid) or N-H (sharper)\n~3000 | C-H (sp3 slightly below 3000, sp2 slightly above)\n~2200 | C triple bond C or C triple bond N (often weak)\n~1700-1750 | C=O carbonyl: esters ~1735, ketones ~1715, COOH broad with OH overtone\n~1600 | C=C (aromatic or alkene)\n~1000-1300 | C-O single bond'},{t:'formula',x:'1H NMR chemical shifts (ppm, TMS = 0):\nsp3 C-H | 0.5-2 ppm\nAlpha to carbonyl | 2-3 ppm\nAlkene C-H | 5-7 ppm\nAromatic C-H | 6.5-8 ppm\nAldehyde C-H | 9-10 ppm\nCarboxylic acid O-H | 10-12 ppm'},{t:'list',x:['Splitting (n+1 rule): a proton with n equivalent neighboring protons splits into n+1 peaks (doublet = 1 neighbor, triplet = 2, quartet = 3).','Integration: area under each peak is proportional to the number of protons in that environment.','Chemical shift = deshielding: electronegative substituents and pi systems pull electron density away and increase the shift.','13C NMR: each chemically unique carbon gives one peak; no splitting in proton-decoupled spectra.','Mass spectrometry: M+ = molecular ion (mass = molecular weight). Fragmentation pattern provides structural clues. Base peak = most abundant fragment.','C=O IR stretch near 1700 cm-1 is the single most diagnostic peak for carbonyl-containing compounds.']},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'For IR: C=O at ~1700 cm-1 is most diagnostic. Broad O-H at ~3300 cm-1 signals alcohol or carboxylic acid. N-H near 3300 is sharper than O-H. No peak at 3300 and a carbonyl at 1735 = ester. For NMR: aldehyde proton at 9-10 ppm is unique. Aromatic protons at 6.5-8 ppm with integration matching ring count confirm benzene ring. Splitting pattern identifies adjacent proton count.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'An unknown compound shows a broad IR absorption at ~3300 cm-1 and a carbonyl stretch at ~1715 cm-1. Which functional group is most consistent?',choices:['A) Ester','B) Aldehyde','C) Carboxylic acid','D) Amide'],answer:2,why:'Carboxylic acids show both a broad O-H stretch (~3300 cm-1, often extending to 2500 cm-1) and a carbonyl stretch ~1710-1725 cm-1. Esters lack the broad O-H peak. Aldehydes lack the broad O-H. Amides show N-H (sharper) and lower carbonyl (~1650-1680 cm-1).'}]},{id:'3.6',num:'3.6',title:'3.6 Biological Organic Chemistry',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Biological molecules (amino acids, carbohydrates, lipids, nucleic acids) are tested on structure and functional group recognition. Mechanisms connecting these to biochemical pathways are covered in Book 6 (Biochemistry). This section provides structural anchors.'},{t:'list',x:['Amino acids: 20 standard; each is an alpha-amino acid (amino and carboxyl groups on the same carbon); all chiral (L-configuration by Fischer convention) except glycine (no stereocenter).','Peptide bond: amide linkage formed between COOH of one amino acid and NH2 of the next; trans configuration preferred (due to partial double-bond character from resonance); restricted rotation.','Isoelectric point (pI): pH at which the amino acid has zero net charge. For amino acids with nonionizable R groups: pI = (pKa1 + pKa2)/2.','Carbohydrates: aldoses have aldehyde group; ketoses have ketone group. D/L designation by Fischer projection (OH on right at highest-numbered stereocenter = D).','Alpha/beta anomers: differ only at the anomeric carbon (C1 in glucose; former carbonyl carbon). In Haworth projection of D-glucose: alpha = anomeric OH down, beta = anomeric OH up.','Beta-glucose builds cellulose (humans lack cellulase). Alpha-glucose builds starch and glycogen (digestible by amylase).','Glycosidic bond: formed between anomeric C-OH and another alcohol with loss of water; links monosaccharides.','Reducing sugar: has a free anomeric carbon capable of opening to aldehyde/ketone form. Glucose, fructose, lactose, and maltose are reducing. Sucrose is NOT (both anomeric carbons locked in glycosidic bond).','Triglycerides: glycerol backbone + 3 fatty acid ester linkages. Hydrolysis (saponification with NaOH) gives glycerol + fatty acid salts (soaps).','Phospholipids: amphipathic (polar phosphate head, nonpolar FA tails); form bilayer membranes.','Steroids: 4 fused rings (3 cyclohexane + 1 cyclopentane); cholesterol is precursor to steroid hormones and bile acids.','Saturated fatty acids: no C=C; solid at room temperature (animal fats). Unsaturated: one or more C=C; liquid (oils). Trans-FA from partial hydrogenation; associated with cardiovascular disease.','Nucleotides: base + sugar + phosphate. Phosphodiester bond links 3\' of one nucleotide to 5\' of the next.']},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'ALPHA vs BETA ANOMERS: Anomers differ ONLY at the anomeric carbon (C1 in glucose, the former carbonyl carbon). In a standard Haworth projection of a D-sugar: ALPHA has the anomeric -OH pointing down (same side as the ring oxygen, trans to C6/CH2OH of glucose). BETA has the anomeric -OH pointing up. Beta-glucose links in cellulose (beta-1,4 linkage); alpha-glucose links in starch/glycogen (alpha-1,4 linkage). Humans have alpha-amylase but not cellulase.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Peptide bond is an amide bond: planar, partial double-bond character, trans preferred. Reducing sugars have free anomeric OH (can open to aldehyde). Sucrose is the only common disaccharide that is NOT a reducing sugar. pI for simple amino acids = average of the two pKa values flanking the zwitterion form.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Why is sucrose a non-reducing sugar while maltose is a reducing sugar?',choices:['A) Sucrose contains only fructose units; maltose contains only glucose units.','B) Sucrose has both anomeric carbons locked in the glycosidic bond; maltose has one free anomeric carbon.','C) Sucrose cannot be hydrolyzed; maltose can be hydrolyzed by amylase.','D) Sucrose is a ketose; maltose is an aldose.'],answer:1,why:'A reducing sugar requires a free anomeric carbon that can open to the aldehyde (or ketone) form and reduce an oxidizing agent. In sucrose, the glycosidic bond is between the anomeric C1 of glucose and the anomeric C2 of fructose, locking both; no free anomeric carbon exists. Maltose has glucose linked alpha-1,4 with a free C1 anomeric OH on the second glucose.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Orgo on the MCAT is mechanism and stereochemistry, not synthesis.',
 nextHint:'Part V continues with Physics: mechanics, fluids, electricity, and waves.',
},
{
 n:4,
 title:'Physics: High-Yield Compression',
 subtitle:'Part V of IX',
 tag:'Physics Review',
 foundational:'mechanics, fluids, electricity, waves, optics, modern physics',
 buildsOn:'Part IV (Organic Chemistry Review)',
 setsUp:'Part VI (Psych/Soc Review)',
 objectives:['Apply kinematics equations and Newton\'s laws to motion problems.','Use work-energy theorem and momentum conservation to analyze collisions.','Apply Bernoulli, Archimedes, and Poiseuille to fluid systems.','Solve wave, Doppler, and optics problems using core equations.','Set up circuits using Ohm\'s law, Kirchhoff\'s rules, and capacitor/resistor combos.','Distinguish photoelectric effect behavior by frequency vs. intensity and apply half-life decay.'],
 opener:'Physics on the MCAT spans classical mechanics through modern atomic theory. The testable core is a tight set of equations and the physical intuition behind them: what happens to the answer when one variable doubles, halves, or goes to zero. This chapter compresses kinematics, forces, energy, fluids, waves, optics, electrostatics, circuits, and modern physics into formula-forward blocks with the key discriminators that separate correct answers from traps.',
 pinnedDisc:{label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Photoelectric effect: FREQUENCY (not intensity) determines whether electrons are ejected and their maximum kinetic energy. Intensity determines how many electrons are ejected once threshold frequency is met. This distinction established light as quantized (photons) and refuted classical wave predictions.'},
 sections:[{id:'4.1',num:'4.1',title:'4.1 Mechanics: Kinematics, Forces, Energy, and Momentum',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Mechanics covers motion description (kinematics), causes of motion (Newton\'s laws), energy accounting (work-energy), and collision analysis (momentum). These topics appear together because forces cause acceleration, acceleration changes velocity, and velocity changes energy and momentum.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Kinematics: v^2 = v0^2 + 2a*dx and projectile independence of x and y. Newton\'s 2nd: F_net = ma. Work-energy: W_net = dKE. Momentum: p = mv, conserved in isolated systems. Rotational: L = I*omega, conserved when no external torque.'},{t:'formula',x:'Kinematics (constant a): v = v0 + at | x = x0 + v0*t + (1/2)*a*t^2 | v^2 = v0^2 + 2*a*dx | x = x0 + (v + v0)*t/2'},{t:'list',x:['Displacement dx is a vector; distance is scalar (total path length).','Free fall: a = -g = -9.8 m/s^2 downward; ignore air resistance unless told otherwise.','Projectile motion: ax = 0, ay = -g; x and y components are independent.','Max range on level ground at 45 degrees launch angle; time to apex = v0*sin(theta)/g.']},{t:'formula',x:'Newton\'s laws: F_net = ma | W = mg | N (on incline) = mg*cos(theta) | friction f = mu*N'},{t:'list',x:['Newton\'s 1st: F_net = 0 means constant velocity (inertia).','Newton\'s 3rd: action-reaction pairs are equal, opposite, and act on DIFFERENT objects.','Static friction (mu_s) is greater than or equal to kinetic friction (mu_k).','Tension is the same magnitude throughout a massless rope.']},{t:'formula',x:'Energy: KE = (1/2)*m*v^2 | PE_grav = mgh | PE_spring = (1/2)*k*x^2 (Hooke: F = -kx) | W = F*d*cos(theta) | W_net = dKE | P = W/t = F*v'},{t:'list',x:['Only the force component along displacement does work.','Conservation of mechanical energy (no friction): KE + PE = constant.','Efficiency = useful output / total input x 100%.']},{t:'formula',x:'Momentum: p = mv | J = F*dt = dp | elastic: KE and p conserved | inelastic: p conserved only | perfectly inelastic: objects stick, max KE loss'},{t:'formula',x:'Rotation: v = r*omega | a_t = r*alpha | a_c = v^2/r = omega^2*r | F_c = m*v^2/r | tau = r*F*sin(theta) | I = sum(m*r^2) | L = I*omega | KE_rot = (1/2)*I*omega^2'},{t:'list',x:['Centripetal force points toward the center of circular motion.','Equilibrium requires both sum(F) = 0 and sum(tau) = 0.','Angular momentum L is conserved when no net external torque: ice skater pulls arms in, omega increases.']}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A ball is launched horizontally from a 20 m cliff at 10 m/s. Ignoring air resistance, approximately how long does it take to hit the ground?',choices:['A) 1.0 s','B) 1.4 s','C) 2.0 s','D) 2.8 s'],answer:2,why:'Vertical: h = (1/2)*g*t^2 so t = sqrt(2h/g) = sqrt(40/9.8) = sqrt(4.08) = about 2.0 s. Horizontal velocity does not affect fall time.'},{stem:'A 2 kg block slides without friction down a ramp from rest at height 5 m. What is its speed at the bottom?',choices:['A) 5 m/s','B) 7 m/s','C) 10 m/s','D) 14 m/s'],answer:2,why:'Conservation of energy: mgh = (1/2)*m*v^2, so v = sqrt(2*g*h) = sqrt(2*9.8*5) = sqrt(98) = about 10 m/s.'}]},{id:'4.2',num:'4.2',title:'4.2 Fluids and Thermodynamics',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Fluid behavior on the MCAT centers on pressure, buoyancy, and flow. Bernoulli and Poiseuille are high-yield because they underlie cardiovascular physiology. Thermodynamics adds the energy accounting for heat engines.'},{t:'formula',x:'Density: rho = m/V (kg/m^3) | Pressure: P = F/A (Pa) | Hydrostatic: P = P0 + rho*g*h | 1 atm = 101 kPa = 760 mmHg'},{t:'list',x:['Water density: 1000 kg/m^3 = 1 g/cm^3. Specific gravity SG = rho/rho_water.','Pascal\'s principle: pressure applied to enclosed fluid transmits equally in all directions. Hydraulic press: F1/A1 = F2/A2.','Archimedes: buoyant force = weight of fluid displaced. F_b = rho_fluid * V_submerged * g.','Floating condition: rho_object < rho_fluid; fraction submerged = rho_object / rho_fluid.']},{t:'formula',x:'Continuity (incompressible): A1*v1 = A2*v2 | Bernoulli: P + (1/2)*rho*v^2 + rho*g*h = constant | Poiseuille: Q = pi*r^4*dP / (8*eta*L)'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Bernoulli: faster flow means LOWER pressure (trade-off between kinetic and pressure energy). Poiseuille: flow Q is proportional to r^4, so halving vessel radius reduces flow 16-fold. This is why vascular stenosis has such large effects on blood flow.'},{t:'list',x:['Viscosity eta (internal friction): water ~1 cP, blood ~3-4 cP.','Reynolds number Re = rho*v*D/eta: high Re predicts turbulent flow.','Surface tension: cohesive forces at liquid-gas interface; drives capillary rise in narrow tubes.']}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Water flows through a pipe that narrows from radius 2 cm to radius 1 cm. If flow speed in the wide section is 1 m/s, what is the speed in the narrow section?',choices:['A) 1 m/s','B) 2 m/s','C) 4 m/s','D) 8 m/s'],answer:2,why:'Continuity: A1*v1 = A2*v2. Area scales as r^2, so A1/A2 = (2/1)^2 = 4. Therefore v2 = v1*(A1/A2) = 1*4 = 4 m/s.'}]},{id:'4.3',num:'4.3',title:'4.3 Waves, Sound, and Optics',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Waves carry energy without net mass transport. Sound is a longitudinal wave; light is transverse. Optics uses the same thin-lens/mirror equation regardless of whether a lens or mirror is involved, with sign conventions carrying the load.'},{t:'formula',x:'Wave basics: v = f*lambda | T = 1/f | Intensity: I = P/A | Decibels: beta = 10*log(I/I0), I0 = 10^-12 W/m^2'},{t:'list',x:['Transverse wave: displacement perpendicular to propagation (light, string).','Longitudinal wave: displacement parallel to propagation (sound).','Sound speed increases in denser, less compressible media: faster in solids than gases.']},{t:'formula',x:'Doppler: f\' = f*(v +/- v_observer) / (v -/+ v_source) | approaching: higher f | receding: lower f'},{t:'list',x:['Standing waves on string (both ends fixed): lambda_n = 2L/n, f_n = n*v/(2L).','Open pipe (both ends open): f_n = n*v/(2L). Closed-open pipe: f_n = n*v/(4L), odd n only.','Beats: beat frequency = |f1 - f2|.','Constructive interference: in phase, path difference = n*lambda. Destructive: path difference = (n + 1/2)*lambda.']},{t:'formula',x:'Optics: reflection: angle_i = angle_r | Snell\'s law: n1*sin(theta1) = n2*sin(theta2), n = c/v | Thin lens/mirror: 1/f = 1/d_o + 1/d_i | m = -d_i/d_o = h_i/h_o'},{t:'list',x:['Total internal reflection: occurs from denser to less dense medium beyond critical angle. theta_c = arcsin(n2/n1).','Converging lens (convex): f > 0; forms real image if object is beyond f.','Diverging lens (concave): always virtual, upright, smaller image.','Concave mirror: converging (f > 0). Convex mirror: diverging (f < 0), always virtual, upright, smaller.','Lens power P = 1/f in diopters (m^-1).','Double-slit: bright fringe at d*sin(theta) = m*lambda. Diffraction greatest when slit width is approximately equal to lambda.']},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD: Lens/Mirror Image Table',x:'Converging lens, object beyond 2f: real, inverted, smaller. | At 2f: real, inverted, same size. | Between f and 2f: real, inverted, larger. | Inside f: virtual, upright, larger (magnifier). | Diverging lens, any distance: virtual, upright, smaller.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'An ambulance moving toward a stationary observer emits a 500 Hz siren. The observer hears a frequency that is:',choices:['A) Lower than 500 Hz','B) Equal to 500 Hz','C) Higher than 500 Hz','D) Zero, because the source is moving'],answer:2,why:'Doppler effect: source approaching a stationary observer increases the observed frequency above the emitted frequency. f\' = f*(v)/(v - v_source) > f when v_source > 0.'}]},{id:'4.4',num:'4.4',title:'4.4 Electricity and Magnetism',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'E and M covers electrostatics (Coulomb, field, potential), circuit analysis (Ohm, Kirchhoff, power), and magnetic forces. RC circuits are commonly tested because they combine capacitors and resistors with time-dependent behavior.'},{t:'formula',x:'Electrostatics: F = k*q1*q2/r^2 (k = 8.99e9 N*m^2/C^2) | E = F/q = k*q/r^2 (N/C or V/m) | V = k*q/r | PE = q*V | W = q*dV'},{t:'list',x:['Electric field points from positive to negative charge.','Positive test charge accelerates toward lower potential.','Parallel plate capacitor: E = V/d (uniform); C = epsilon*A/d; Q = C*V; U = (1/2)*C*V^2.','Capacitors in series: 1/C_eq = sum(1/Ci). In parallel: C_eq = sum(Ci).']},{t:'formula',x:'Circuits: I = dQ/dt | V = IR (Ohm\'s law) | R = rho*L/A | P = IV = I^2*R = V^2/R | Series R: R_eq = sum(Ri) | Parallel R: 1/R_eq = sum(1/Ri)'},{t:'list',x:['Kirchhoff\'s current rule: sum of currents into a node = sum out.','Kirchhoff\'s voltage rule: sum of voltage changes around any closed loop = 0.','Capacitors in parallel add (more area); resistors in series add (more length). These are opposite configurations.']},{t:'formula',x:'RC circuit: charging V_C = V0*(1 - exp(-t/RC)) | discharging V_C = V0*exp(-t/RC) | time constant tau = RC | Capacitor at DC steady state: open circuit | Inductor at DC steady state: wire (short circuit)'},{t:'formula',x:'Magnetism: F = q*v*B*sin(theta) (perpendicular to v and B) | F on wire = I*L*B*sin(theta) | Flux: Phi = B*A*cos(theta) | Faraday: EMF = -dPhi/dt | Transformer: V_p/V_s = N_p/N_s | I_p/I_s = N_s/N_p'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Capacitor behavior by frequency: capacitor blocks DC (acts as open circuit at steady state) but passes high-frequency AC. Inductor: opposite -- passes DC (acts as wire) but blocks high-frequency AC. On MCAT, identify which component is which and what happens long after the switch closes (capacitor fully charged, no current through it).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Three identical resistors R are connected in parallel. The equivalent resistance of the combination is:',choices:['A) 3R','B) R','C) R/3','D) R/9'],answer:2,why:'1/R_eq = 1/R + 1/R + 1/R = 3/R, so R_eq = R/3. Parallel resistors always yield an equivalent resistance less than the smallest individual resistor.'},{stem:'A magnetic force on a positive charge moving with velocity v in field B is directed:',choices:['A) Parallel to v','B) Parallel to B','C) Perpendicular to both v and B','D) Opposite to v'],answer:2,why:'F = q*v x B. The cross product is always perpendicular to both vectors. This means magnetic force does no work on the charge (force perpendicular to displacement).'}]},{id:'4.5',num:'4.5',title:'4.5 Modern Physics and Nuclear Decay',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Modern physics covers quantization of light and matter, atomic structure, and nuclear decay. The photoelectric effect and half-life calculations are the most commonly tested topics in this section.'},{t:'formula',x:'Photon energy: E = h*f = h*c/lambda (h = 6.626e-34 J*s) | Photoelectric: KE_max = h*f - phi (phi = work function) | de Broglie: lambda = h/p = h/(m*v) | Uncertainty: dx*dp >= h-bar/2'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Photoelectric effect: FREQUENCY determines whether electrons are ejected (must exceed threshold) and their maximum KE (KE_max = hf - phi). INTENSITY determines how many electrons are ejected (more photons, more electrons), but not their energy. Classical physics predicted intensity would control electron energy -- the opposite of what experiment showed.'},{t:'list',x:['Intensity increases electron count but NOT energy per electron.','de Broglie wavelength is significant only for very small masses (electrons, protons).','Heisenberg: position and momentum cannot both be known precisely at the same time.']},{t:'formula',x:'Nuclear decay: half-life N = N0*(1/2)^n, where n = number of half-lives | t = t_half * n | Mass-energy: E = dm*c^2 (binding energy from mass defect)'},{t:'list',x:['Alpha decay: emits He-4 nucleus; mass number -4, atomic number -2.','Beta minus decay: n to p + e- + antineutrino; atomic number +1, mass unchanged.','Beta plus (positron) decay: p to n + e+ + neutrino; atomic number -1.','Gamma decay: photon emission only; no change in Z or A.','Electron capture: p + e- to n; atomic number -1.','Fission: heavy nucleus splits (U-235). Fusion: light nuclei combine (sun). Both release energy via mass defect.']},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD: Nuclear Decay Summary',x:'Alpha: -4 mass, -2 atomic number. Beta minus: +1 atomic number, mass same. Beta plus: -1 atomic number, mass same. Gamma: no change in Z or A. Electron capture: -1 atomic number. All decay modes reduce nuclear instability.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A radioactive isotope has a half-life of 10 years. After 30 years, what fraction of the original sample remains?',choices:['A) 1/2','B) 1/4','C) 1/8','D) 1/16'],answer:2,why:'30 years = 3 half-lives. N = N0*(1/2)^3 = N0/8. Each half-life halves the remaining amount, so three half-lives gives one-eighth.'},{stem:'In the photoelectric effect, doubling the intensity of light while keeping frequency above threshold will:',choices:['A) Double the maximum kinetic energy of ejected electrons','B) Double the number of ejected electrons','C) Have no effect on electron ejection','D) Reduce the number of ejected electrons'],answer:1,why:'Intensity (number of photons) determines how many electrons are ejected, not their energy. KE_max = hf - phi depends only on frequency. Doubling intensity doubles the photon count and thus doubles the electron count.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Physics equations are tools: know what each variable does to the answer.',
 nextHint:'Part VI continues with Psychology and Sociology: behavior, society, and health.',
},
{
 n:5,
 title:'Psychology and Sociology: High-Yield Compression',
 subtitle:'Part VI of IX',
 tag:'Psych/Soc Review',
 foundational:'behavior, cognition, development, social psychology, sociology, health',
 buildsOn:'Part V (Physics Review)',
 setsUp:'Part VII (Biochemistry Review)',
 objectives:['Distinguish classical from operant conditioning and identify the four operant consequence types.','Trace the memory pathway from sensory register through long-term storage and name the brain regions responsible.','Apply Piaget, Erikson, and Kohlberg stages to clinical vignettes about development.','Identify the three attribution errors and predict their direction in a given scenario.','Connect sociological stratification, SES, and health disparities to clinical outcomes.','Apply the biopsychosocial model to explain illness presentation and treatment planning.'],
 opener:'Psychology and Sociology on the MCAT tests mechanisms, not vocabulary lists. Every question stems from a research scenario or clinical vignette that asks you to predict behavior, interpret a study finding, or connect a social factor to a health outcome. This chapter compresses the six highest-yield domains: sensation and perception, learning and memory, cognition and motivation, personality and disorders, social psychology, and sociology. The discriminators between nearly identical concepts, like classical versus operant conditioning or James-Lange versus Cannon-Bard, account for a disproportionate share of points. Master those distinctions first, then build outward.',
 pinnedDisc:{label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Classical conditioning pairs two STIMULI to produce a reflexive, ELICITED response (organism reacts). Operant conditioning pairs a BEHAVIOR with a consequence to change its frequency; the behavior is VOLUNTARY and EMITTED (organism acts). Classical: bell + food causes salivation; operant: lever press + food reward increases pressing.'},
 sections:[{id:'5.1',num:'5.1',title:'5.1 Biobehavioral Foundations: Sensation, Perception, and Learning',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Sensation is detection at the receptor level (transduction of a stimulus into a neural signal). Perception is CNS interpretation of that signal. The gap between them is where top-down expectations and Gestalt rules operate.'},{t:'list',x:['Absolute threshold: minimum stimulus detectable 50% of the time.','Difference threshold (JND): smallest detectable change between two stimuli.','Weber\'s law: delta-I / I = constant; perceived change is proportional, not absolute.','Signal detection theory: outcome depends on sensitivity AND criterion (motivation, expectation) -- four outcomes: hit, miss, false alarm, correct rejection.','Sensory adaptation: decreased response to a constant, ongoing stimulus.','Vision: rods (low light, peripheral, no color) vs cones (color, central, fovea); transduction in retina.','Hearing: cochlea and hair cells; high frequency at base, low frequency at apex (place theory).','Smell: olfactory bulb; one of the few senses NOT routed through the thalamus.','Top-down processing: concept-driven; expectations shape what is perceived.','Bottom-up processing: data-driven; starts from raw sensory input.','Gestalt principles: figure-ground, proximity, similarity, continuity, closure.']},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'CLASSICAL vs OPERANT: Classical pairs two stimuli; the response is REFLEXIVE and ELICITED (Pavlov: bell + food leads to bell alone causing salivation). Operant pairs a behavior with a consequence; the behavior is VOLUNTARY and EMITTED (Skinner: rat presses lever, gets food, presses more). Key test cue: if the organism has no choice in the response, it is classical. If the organism chooses to act, it is operant.'},{t:'formula',x:'LEARNING TYPES\n| Type                   | Mechanism                              | Classic Example              |\n|------------------------|----------------------------------------|------------------------------|\n| Classical conditioning | Pair neutral + US; CS elicits CR       | Pavlov bell + food           |\n| Operant conditioning   | Behavior shaped by consequences        | Skinner box lever press      |\n| Observational learning | Watching others (Bandura)              | Bobo doll experiment         |\n| Habituation            | Decreased response to repeated stim   | Tuning out clock ticking     |\n| Sensitization          | Increased response after intense stim  | Startle after loud noise     |'},{t:'formula',x:'OPERANT CONSEQUENCES\n| Consequence             | Effect on behavior | What is added or removed          |\n|-------------------------|--------------------|-----------------------------------|\n| Positive reinforcement  | Increases          | Adds desirable stimulus (treat)   |\n| Negative reinforcement  | Increases          | Removes aversive (seatbelt beep)  |\n| Positive punishment     | Decreases          | Adds aversive (scolding)          |\n| Negative punishment     | Decreases          | Removes desirable (timeout)       |'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Reinforcement schedules: Fixed ratio = high rate with brief pause after each reinforcement. Variable ratio = highest and most persistent response rate (gambling model). Fixed interval = scalloped pattern. Variable interval = steady moderate rate. Variable ratio is MOST RESISTANT to extinction.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A researcher pairs a tone with a puff of air to the eye until the tone alone causes blinking. Which type of learning is demonstrated, and is the blink reflexive or voluntary?',choices:['A) Operant conditioning; voluntary','B) Classical conditioning; reflexive','C) Observational learning; reflexive','D) Operant conditioning; reflexive'],answer:1,why:'A tone (neutral stimulus) is paired with an air puff (US) until the tone alone elicits blinking (CR). The blink is a reflex, not a chosen action. This is classical conditioning by definition.'},{stem:'A slot machine pays out after an unpredictable number of pulls. Which reinforcement schedule does this represent, and why is it hardest to extinguish?',choices:['A) Fixed interval; the payout is predictable','B) Fixed ratio; every nth response is reinforced','C) Variable ratio; reinforcement is unpredictable after an unknown number of responses','D) Variable interval; reinforcement occurs after an unpredictable time period'],answer:2,why:'Variable ratio schedules reinforce after an unpredictable number of responses. Because the next reinforcement could always be one response away, the behavior persists even when reinforcement stops, making it the schedule most resistant to extinction.'}]},{id:'5.2',num:'5.2',title:'5.2 Memory, Cognition, and Consciousness',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Memory is a three-stage system: encoding, storage, retrieval. Failure at any stage produces forgetting. Long-term memory divides into explicit (declarative) and implicit types, each with distinct brain substrates.'},{t:'formula',x:'MEMORY STAGES\n| Stage           | Capacity          | Duration          | Notes                          |\n|-----------------|-------------------|-------------------|--------------------------------|\n| Sensory         | Large, modality-specific | ~250 ms iconic; ~3 s echoic | Iconic = visual; echoic = auditory |\n| Short-term (WM) | 7 +/- 2 items     | ~20-30 s          | Miller\'s number; rehearsal extends |\n| Long-term       | Essentially unlimited | Essentially unlimited | Semantic > phonemic > visual encoding |'},{t:'list',x:['Explicit (declarative): episodic (autobiographical events) and semantic (facts, concepts).','Implicit: procedural (skills, habits) and priming.','Hippocampus: forms new explicit memories; damage causes anterograde amnesia.','Cerebellum and basal ganglia: implicit/procedural memory.','Amygdala: emotional memory; modulates hippocampal consolidation under stress.','LTP (long-term potentiation): NMDA receptors in hippocampus; cellular basis of learning and memory.','Proactive interference: old memories block encoding of new ones.','Retroactive interference: new memories disrupt retrieval of old ones.','Retrieval failure: information is stored but inaccessible (tip-of-tongue state).','Mnemonics: method of loci, chunking, hierarchical organization.']},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'PROACTIVE vs RETROACTIVE INTERFERENCE: Proactive = old learning BLOCKS new (the past intrudes forward). Retroactive = new learning BLOCKS old (the new disrupts the past looking backward). Memory aid: pro = forward (old pushing into new); retro = backward (new pushing into old).'},{t:'p',x:'Cognition covers problem solving, heuristics, language, and thought. Algorithms guarantee a correct solution through systematic search; heuristics are mental shortcuts that are fast but prone to bias.'},{t:'list',x:['Availability heuristic: judge likelihood by how easily examples come to mind.','Representativeness heuristic: judge by similarity to a prototype.','Anchoring bias: over-rely on the first piece of information encountered.','Confirmation bias: seek information that confirms existing beliefs.','Hindsight bias: after learning the outcome, believe you predicted it.','Functional fixedness: inability to perceive novel uses for an object.','Language structure: phoneme (sound) to morpheme (meaning unit) to syntax (grammar) to semantics (meaning) to pragmatics (context).','Whorf hypothesis (linguistic relativity): language shapes thought; strong form is controversial.','Critical period for language acquisition: birth to puberty.']},{t:'p',x:'Consciousness and states: waking, sleep stages (N1, N2, N3 slow-wave, REM), hypnosis, meditation, and drug-altered states. REM is associated with dreaming and memory consolidation; slow-wave (N3) is deepest restorative sleep.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Hippocampus stores new EXPLICIT memories. Cerebellum and basal ganglia store IMPLICIT/PROCEDURAL. Amygdala stores EMOTIONAL. LTP via NMDA receptors is the cellular mechanism. Anterograde amnesia = cannot form new memories (hippocampal damage); retrograde amnesia = cannot access old memories.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient with bilateral hippocampal damage can still ride a bicycle learned before the injury but cannot remember meeting her physician five minutes earlier. Which dissociation does this illustrate?',choices:['A) Retrograde amnesia for procedural memory; anterograde amnesia for episodic memory','B) Anterograde amnesia for explicit memory; intact implicit/procedural memory','C) Proactive interference blocking new semantic memories','D) Retroactive interference from old episodic memories'],answer:1,why:'The hippocampus is required for forming new explicit (declarative) memories. Procedural memory (riding a bicycle) depends on the cerebellum and basal ganglia, which are intact. This is the classic anterograde amnesia pattern with preserved implicit memory.'}]},{id:'5.3',num:'5.3',title:'5.3 Development, Motivation, Emotion, Personality, and Disorders',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Development spans cognitive (Piaget), psychosocial (Erikson), and moral (Kohlberg) dimensions. MCAT vignettes describe a child or adult and ask which stage best explains the behavior.'},{t:'formula',x:'PIAGET COGNITIVE STAGES\n| Stage               | Age      | Key Features                                   |\n|---------------------|----------|------------------------------------------------|\n| Sensorimotor        | 0-2      | Object permanence; learning through senses/action |\n| Preoperational      | 2-7      | Egocentrism; symbolic play; no conservation    |\n| Concrete operational| 7-11     | Conservation; logical on tangible objects       |\n| Formal operational  | 12+      | Abstract reasoning; hypothetical thinking       |'},{t:'list',x:['Vygotsky: zone of proximal development (ZPD); learning is fundamentally social, mediated by more capable others.','Kohlberg moral development: preconventional (self-interest), conventional (rules and social order), postconventional (abstract principles).','Erikson psychosocial stages: eight stages from trust vs mistrust (infancy) to integrity vs despair (late adulthood).']},{t:'formula',x:'MOTIVATION AND EMOTION THEORIES\n| Theory                        | Sequence                                                          |\n|-------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Drive-reduction               | Physiological need creates drive; behavior reduces drive           |\n| Yerkes-Dodson (arousal)       | Optimal performance at moderate arousal; lower optimum for hard tasks |\n| Maslow hierarchy              | Physiological, safety, love/belonging, esteem, self-actualization  |\n| Incentive theory              | External rewards motivate; overjustification reduces intrinsic motivation |'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'JAMES-LANGE vs CANNON-BARD vs SCHACHTER-SINGER: James-Lange: body response PRECEDES emotion (run, then feel fear). Cannon-Bard: body and emotion occur SIMULTANEOUSLY and independently. Schachter-Singer (two-factor): arousal PLUS a cognitive label produce emotion. Key test: if body first then emotion = James-Lange; if simultaneous = Cannon-Bard; if cognitive label required = Schachter-Singer.'},{t:'p',x:'Personality theories: trait (Big Five OCEAN), psychoanalytic (Freud id/ego/superego + defense mechanisms), humanistic (Rogers/Maslow unconditional positive regard), social-cognitive (Bandura reciprocal determinism and self-efficacy), behaviorist (personality as learned behaviors).'},{t:'formula',x:'PSYCHOLOGICAL DISORDER CATEGORIES (DSM-5)\n| Category                    | Key Examples                                                   |\n|-----------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Mood                        | Major depressive, bipolar, persistent depressive               |\n| Anxiety                     | GAD, panic disorder, phobias, social anxiety                   |\n| OCD and related             | OCD, body dysmorphic, hoarding                                 |\n| Trauma                      | PTSD, acute stress disorder                                    |\n| Dissociative                | Dissociative identity, depersonalization                       |\n| Psychotic                   | Schizophrenia: positive (hallucinations, delusions), negative (flat affect, avolition) |\n| Personality                 | Cluster A (odd), B (dramatic: antisocial, borderline, histrionic, narcissistic), C (anxious) |\n| Neurodevelopmental          | ADHD, autism spectrum, intellectual disability                 |\n| Eating                      | Anorexia, bulimia, binge eating                                |'},{t:'list',x:['Biological correlates: depression = low serotonin and NE; schizophrenia = elevated dopamine; Alzheimer = low ACh; Parkinson = low dopamine.','Defense mechanisms (Freud): repression, projection, displacement, sublimation, rationalization, regression.','Big Five OCEAN: Openness, Conscientiousness, Extraversion, Agreeableness, Neuroticism.','Therapy options: psychodynamic (unconscious insight), behavioral (desensitization/exposure), CBT (most evidence-based), humanistic (client-centered), biomedical (SSRIs, antipsychotics, lithium, benzodiazepines, ECT).']},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Schizophrenia: POSITIVE symptoms = excess function added (hallucinations, delusions, disorganized speech). NEGATIVE symptoms = function lost (flat affect, avolition, alogia). Dopamine hypothesis links elevated DA to positive symptoms. Antipsychotics block D2 receptors.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 5-year-old shown two equal balls of clay insists the elongated one has more clay after it is rolled out. Which Piagetian concept explains this, and in which stage is this child?',choices:['A) Object permanence; sensorimotor stage','B) Lack of conservation; preoperational stage','C) Lack of abstract reasoning; formal operational stage','D) Egocentrism; concrete operational stage'],answer:1,why:'Conservation is the understanding that quantity stays constant despite changes in shape. Children in the preoperational stage (ages 2-7) lack this ability. The child judging by appearance instead of logic is a classic preoperational finding.'},{stem:'After receiving a bonus at work, an employee who previously painted for personal enjoyment loses interest in painting once the company starts paying him for it. This best illustrates which concept?',choices:['A) Drive-reduction theory','B) Overjustification effect','C) Yerkes-Dodson law','D) Maslow\'s hierarchy'],answer:1,why:'The overjustification effect states that adding extrinsic rewards for an intrinsically motivated behavior reduces intrinsic motivation. The employee attributed his painting to external payment rather than personal enjoyment, undermining the original intrinsic drive.'}]},{id:'5.4',num:'5.4',title:'5.4 Social Psychology',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Social psychology examines how individuals think about, influence, and relate to others. MCAT questions often present a study design and ask you to name the bias or group phenomenon it demonstrates.'},{t:'formula',x:'ATTRIBUTION ERRORS\n| Bias                    | Pattern                                                          |\n|-------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Fundamental attribution error | Overestimate dispositional (internal) factors in others\' behavior |\n| Self-serving bias       | Own success = dispositional; own failure = situational           |\n| Actor-observer bias     | Own behavior = situational; others\' behavior = dispositional    |'},{t:'list',x:['Conformity (Asch line studies): individuals match group judgment; conformity increases with group size up to about 5 and with unanimity.','Obedience (Milgram): participants administered apparent shocks to confederates when commanded by an authority figure, even at high intensity.','Bystander effect: as number of bystanders increases, probability that any single individual helps decreases (diffusion of responsibility).','Groupthink: desire for group harmony suppresses dissenting views; poor decisions result.','Group polarization: group discussion pushes attitudes toward a more extreme version of the initial majority position.','Social facilitation: presence of others improves performance on easy or well-practiced tasks; impairs performance on difficult or novel tasks.','Cognitive dissonance: discomfort caused by holding conflicting beliefs or acting against one\'s beliefs; resolved by changing belief, behavior, or perception.','Prejudice = negative attitude; discrimination = differential behavior; stereotype = overgeneralized belief about a group.','Stereotype threat: awareness of a negative stereotype about one\'s group impairs performance under evaluative conditions.']},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'CONFORMITY vs OBEDIENCE: Conformity (Asch) is changing behavior to match a GROUP without a direct order; social pressure is implicit. Obedience (Milgram) is compliance with a direct command from an AUTHORITY figure. Both involve external pressure, but conformity is peer-based and obedience is hierarchy-based.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Fundamental attribution error direction: we see others\' behavior as caused by WHO THEY ARE (dispositional), not their situation. Self-serving bias direction: our own success = our ability; our own failure = bad luck or circumstances. These biases run in opposite directions for self vs other.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A pedestrian collapses on a busy sidewalk. Forty people walk past without helping. A block away on a quiet street, a single passerby immediately stops to assist. Which phenomenon best explains the contrast?',choices:['A) Groupthink','B) Group polarization','C) Bystander effect and diffusion of responsibility','D) Social facilitation'],answer:2,why:'The bystander effect predicts that helping decreases as the number of witnesses increases because responsibility is diffused across the group. The lone passerby bears full perceived responsibility, so helping is more likely.'}]},{id:'5.5',num:'5.5',title:'5.5 Sociology, Stratification, and Health Disparities',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Sociology examines social structure, institutions, and the forces that distribute resources and health across populations. The MCAT tests this through patient scenarios involving SES, race, gender, and access to care.'},{t:'formula',x:'SOCIOLOGICAL THEORIES\n| Theory                          | Core Lens                                                    |\n|---------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Functionalism (Durkheim)        | Society as a system of interrelated parts maintaining stability |\n| Conflict theory (Marx)          | Society as competition over scarce resources; power and inequality |\n| Symbolic interactionism (Mead)  | Micro-level meaning-making through symbols and interactions  |\n| Social constructionism          | Reality is constructed through social processes              |\n| Feminist theory                 | Gender as a key axis of stratification                       |\n| Rational choice                 | Individuals as rational actors maximizing benefit            |'},{t:'list',x:['Socialization agents: family, school, peers, media, workplace.','Ascribed status: assigned at birth (race, sex, caste). Achieved status: earned through effort (degree, occupation). Master status dominates identity.','Role conflict: incompatible demands from different roles (parent and surgeon on call). Role strain: tension within a single role.','Institutions: family, education, religion, economy, government, healthcare.','Stratification systems: class (economic, open), caste (rigid, ascribed, closed), estate (feudal).','Social mobility: vertical (up or down in class hierarchy), horizontal (same level, different position), intergenerational (comparing child to parent class).','Demographic transition: society moves from high birth/high death to high birth/low death to low birth/low death.','Health disparities: systematically worse outcomes by SES, race/ethnicity, gender, and geography.','Sick role (Parsons): patient is exempt from normal duties, not blamed for illness, expected to seek competent care, and expected to want recovery.','Medicalization: redefining non-medical problems as medical conditions (e.g., ADHD, addiction).','Iron triangle of healthcare: cost, access, and quality; improving two tends to compromise the third.']},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'ASCRIBED vs ACHIEVED STATUS: Ascribed status is assigned at birth and cannot be changed by individual action (race, biological sex, caste). Achieved status is earned through action (educational degree, job title, income level). Master status is whichever status most shapes how others perceive the individual, overriding other roles.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'SES and health: lower SES correlates with higher morbidity, mortality, and barriers to care across nearly every condition. Mechanisms include chronic stress (allostatic load), limited access to preventive care, environmental exposures, and reduced health literacy. The biopsychosocial model frames the social layer explicitly: always address social determinants in MCAT clinical vignettes.'},{t:'p',x:'The biopsychosocial model integrates biological (genes, anatomy, biochemistry), psychological (cognition, emotion, behavior), and social (family, culture, SES, access) factors. MCAT questions frequently ask which axis a given factor belongs to or how care fails when one axis is ignored.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A sociologist studies a community where children are born into a permanent social tier that determines occupation, marriage partners, and legal standing, with no legitimate path to upward movement. Which stratification system is described?',choices:['A) Class system','B) Estate system','C) Caste system','D) Achieved status hierarchy'],answer:2,why:'A caste system is a rigid, closed stratification system based on ascribed status at birth. Occupation, marriage, and social position are fixed. Class systems allow social mobility; estate systems are feudal; achieved status hierarchies are open.'},{stem:'A physician notes that her patient, recently diagnosed with a chronic illness, has stopped going to work and expects family members to perform all household tasks. The patient states he should not be blamed because he is ill. According to Parsons, which aspect of the sick role is the patient NOT fulfilling?',choices:['A) Exemption from normal role responsibilities','B) Absence of personal blame for the illness','C) Obligation to seek competent medical care and desire to recover','D) Recognition that illness is an undesirable state'],answer:2,why:'Parsons\' sick role grants exemption from duties and removes blame, but also OBLIGATES the patient to seek care and genuinely want to recover. A patient who uses illness to avoid responsibilities without actively pursuing recovery violates this second set of obligations.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Psych/Soc rewards mechanism over memorized definitions: always ask why the behavior occurs.',
 nextHint:'Part VII continues with Biochemistry: metabolism, genetics, and molecular biology.',
},
{
 n:6,
 title:'Biochemistry: High-Yield Compression',
 subtitle:'Part VII of IX',
 tag:'Biochem Review',
 foundational:'amino acids, enzymes, metabolism, DNA/RNA, lipids, vitamins',
 buildsOn:'Part VI (Psych/Soc Review)',
 setsUp:'Part VIII (Discriminator Index)',
 objectives:['Classify the 20 amino acids by property group and predict protein structure from primary sequence.','Apply Michaelis-Menten kinetics and identify inhibition type from Km, Vmax, and Lineweaver-Burk data.','Trace glucose through glycolysis, PDH, TCA, and the ETC with ATP yields and regulatory points.','Explain fat and nitrogen metabolism including beta-oxidation, urea cycle, and ketone body production.','Distinguish DNA replication, transcription, and translation machinery and the antibiotics that target them.','Link vitamin cofactor roles to their deficiency diseases and fat-soluble vs water-soluble distinctions.'],
 opener:'Biochemistry on the MCAT is metabolic logic. Every pathway has a rate-limiting enzyme, a regulatory signal, and a downstream consequence. Master three layers: structures (amino acid properties, nucleotide bases, lipid classes), kinetics (Km, Vmax, inhibition patterns), and integration (how insulin, glucagon, and cortisol flip anabolic versus catabolic switches). The discriminators in this chapter separate ETC inhibitors from uncouplers, hexokinase from glucokinase, and ketogenic from glucogenic amino acids -- three distinctions that appear repeatedly in passage-based questions.',
 pinnedDisc:{label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'ETC INHIBITORS (rotenone, cyanide) stop electron flow -- gradient collapses, no ATP, O2 consumption falls. UNCOUPLERS (2,4-DNP, thermogenin/UCP1) allow electron flow but H+ leaks back without making ATP -- all energy released as heat, O2 consumption stays HIGH. ATP SYNTHASE INHIBITORS (oligomycin) block the H+ channel -- gradient builds until ETC stalls, both ATP and O2 consumption fall. Watch O2 consumption to tell them apart.'},
 sections:[{id:'6.1',num:'6.1',title:'6.1 Amino Acids and Protein Structure',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'All 20 standard amino acids are L-configuration alpha-amino acids. Glycine is the only one that lacks chirality (R group = H). Memorize property groups because they predict protein folding, active-site chemistry, and disulfide bond formation.'},{t:'list',x:['Nonpolar: G, A, V, L, I, M, F, W, P -- proline is a unique imino acid that kinks alpha-helices.','Polar uncharged: S, T, C, N, Q, Y (tyrosine is aromatic and polar).','Acidic (negative at pH 7.4): D (Asp), E (Glu).','Basic (positive at pH 7.4): K (Lys), R (Arg), H (His; pKa ~6, partially protonated at physiologic pH).','Aromatic: F, W, Y -- all absorb at 280 nm; tryptophan absorbs most strongly.','Sulfur-containing: C (cysteine, forms disulfide bonds), M (methionine).']},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Disulfide bonds (Cys-Cys, -2H) are the ONLY covalent tertiary/quaternary forces. They form only in oxidizing environments (extracellular space, ER lumen). All other tertiary forces are non-covalent: hydrophobic effect (usually dominant), H-bonds, salt bridges, van der Waals.'},{t:'p',x:'Protein structure levels: Primary = peptide bonds (sequence). Secondary = H-bonds on backbone (alpha-helix between i and i+4; beta-sheet between strands; R groups are not involved). Tertiary = 3D fold of one polypeptide. Quaternary = multiple polypeptides held together by non-covalent forces and disulfides.'},{t:'list',x:['Alpha-helix: R groups project outward; proline disrupts the helix (rigid, cannot form the required H-bond).','Beta-sheet: parallel (same N-to-C direction) or antiparallel; R groups alternate above and below.','Denaturation: loss of secondary/tertiary/quaternary structure; PRIMARY is preserved. Caused by heat, extreme pH, detergents, urea.']},{t:'p',x:'Hemoglobin vs myoglobin: Hb has 4 subunits (2alpha 2beta), cooperative O2 binding (sigmoidal curve), allosteric regulation by Bohr effect (CO2/H+) and 2,3-BPG (shifts curve right, decreases O2 affinity). Myoglobin has 1 subunit, non-cooperative binding (hyperbolic curve), and higher O2 affinity than Hb -- functions as muscle O2 storage, not transport.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A researcher places a protein in an oxidizing buffer containing the amino acid cysteine. Which bond type is most likely to form BETWEEN cysteines?',choices:['A) Peptide bond','B) Hydrogen bond','C) Disulfide bond','D) Ionic bond'],answer:2,why:'Disulfide bonds form between cysteine residues in oxidizing environments via loss of 2H. Peptide bonds are formed during translation, not post-translationally between side chains. H-bonds and ionic bonds are non-covalent and do not involve cysteine sulfur atoms specifically.'},{stem:'Which amino acid, if substituted into the middle of an alpha-helix, would most likely disrupt the helical structure?',choices:['A) Alanine','B) Leucine','C) Proline','D) Valine'],answer:2,why:'Proline is an imino acid whose rigid ring structure prevents rotation of the peptide bond and cannot donate an H-bond to the helix backbone, introducing a kink. The others are nonpolar aliphatic amino acids compatible with helix formation.'}]},{id:'6.2',num:'6.2',title:'6.2 Enzyme Kinetics and Inhibition',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Enzymes are biological catalysts: they lower activation energy but do NOT change delta-G, the equilibrium constant, or the equilibrium position. They work by stabilizing the transition state.'},{t:'formula',x:'Michaelis-Menten: V = Vmax[S] / (Km + [S]) | Km = [S] at V = Vmax/2 | Vmax = kcat x [E]total | kcat/Km = catalytic efficiency (diffusion limit ~10^8-10^9 M^-1 s^-1) | Lineweaver-Burk: 1/V = (Km/Vmax)(1/[S]) + 1/Vmax'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Km inversely reflects affinity: LOW Km = HIGH affinity (enzyme binds substrate tightly at low [S]). HIGH Km = LOW affinity (enzyme needs high [S] to reach half-Vmax).'},{t:'p',x:'Inhibition types and their effects on Km and Vmax:'},{t:'list',x:['Competitive: inhibitor binds ACTIVE SITE; competes with substrate. Km increases (apparent), Vmax unchanged (high [S] overcomes it). Lineweaver-Burk: same y-intercept, increased slope, x-intercept moves toward origin.','Noncompetitive (pure): inhibitor binds ALLOSTERIC SITE regardless of [S]. Vmax decreases, Km unchanged. Lineweaver-Burk: same x-intercept, increased y-intercept.','Uncompetitive: inhibitor binds ONLY enzyme-substrate complex. BOTH Vmax and Km decrease (proportionally). Lineweaver-Burk: parallel lines (same slope, increased y-intercept).','Mixed: inhibitor binds enzyme alone or enzyme-substrate complex with different affinities. Vmax decreases, Km may increase or decrease.']},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'UNCOMPETITIVE inhibition is the one that DECREASES both Km and Vmax -- this surprises students. The Km decrease happens because the inhibitor traps the ES complex, making substrate binding appear tighter. Vmax decreases because some ES complex cannot proceed. Parallel lines on Lineweaver-Burk are the visual signature.'},{t:'p',x:'Allosteric regulation: allosteric enzymes show cooperative kinetics (sigmoidal V vs [S] curve instead of hyperbolic). Effectors bind at sites distinct from the active site. Feedback inhibition = end product inhibits the first committed step of its own pathway. Other regulation types: covalent modification (phosphorylation), zymogen activation (zymogens are inactive precursors), gene expression changes, compartmentalization.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'An inhibitor reduces Vmax but does not change Km. On a Lineweaver-Burk plot, which change is observed?',choices:['A) Same y-intercept, increased slope','B) Same x-intercept, increased y-intercept','C) Parallel lines shifted upward','D) Lines intersect on the y-axis'],answer:1,why:'Noncompetitive inhibition decreases Vmax (increases 1/Vmax = y-intercept) without changing Km (x-intercept = -1/Km stays the same). Same x-intercept and a higher y-intercept is the noncompetitive pattern. Option A is competitive; option C is uncompetitive.'}]},{id:'6.3',num:'6.3',title:'6.3 Carbohydrate Metabolism: Glycolysis, TCA, and ETC',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Glycolysis occurs in the cytoplasm. One glucose yields 2 pyruvate, net 2 ATP, and 2 NADH. It is anaerobic-compatible because NADH can be re-oxidized to NAD+ by converting pyruvate to lactate.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Rate-limiting enzyme of glycolysis: PFK-1. Activated by AMP and F-2,6-BP (insulin signal). Inhibited by ATP and citrate. Pyruvate kinase (last step) activated by F-1,6-BP (feed-forward); inhibited by ATP and alanine.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'HEXOKINASE vs GLUCOKINASE: both phosphorylate glucose to G-6-P. Hexokinase (most tissues): low Km (high affinity, works at low glucose), low Vmax, inhibited by G-6-P. Glucokinase (liver and pancreatic beta cells): high Km (low affinity, output scales with blood glucose), high Vmax, NOT inhibited by G-6-P, induced by insulin. Glucokinase acts as a glucose sensor in beta cells -- its high Km is why insulin release scales with blood glucose concentration.'},{t:'p',x:'Pyruvate fate: under anaerobic conditions, pyruvate is reduced to lactate (regenerates NAD+, no O2 required). Under aerobic conditions, pyruvate enters the mitochondria and is converted to acetyl-CoA by pyruvate dehydrogenase (PDH).'},{t:'formula',x:'PDH: pyruvate + NAD+ + CoA → acetyl-CoA + NADH + CO2 | Cofactors: TPP (B1), lipoic acid, CoA (B5), FAD (B2), NAD+ (B3) -- mnemonic "Tender Loving Care For Nancy" (1, Lipoate, 5, 2, 3)'},{t:'list',x:['PDH activated by: ADP, NAD+, Ca2+ (exercise signal).','PDH inhibited by: ATP, NADH, acetyl-CoA (product inhibition).','TCA cycle (citric acid cycle): occurs in mitochondrial matrix.','Per acetyl-CoA: 3 NADH, 1 FADH2, 1 GTP, 2 CO2 released.','Per glucose (2 acetyl-CoA): 6 NADH, 2 FADH2, 2 GTP, 4 CO2.','Rate-limiting step: isocitrate dehydrogenase (also citrate synthase and alpha-ketoglutarate DH are key).','TCA inhibited by ATP, NADH; activated by ADP, NAD+, Ca2+.']},{t:'p',x:'Electron Transport Chain (ETC): inner mitochondrial membrane. Electrons from NADH enter at Complex I; FADH2 enters at CoQ (bypasses Complex I, yields less ATP). Protons are pumped into the intermembrane space creating the electrochemical gradient (chemiosmosis) that drives ATP synthase (Complex V).'},{t:'list',x:['Complex I (NADH dehydrogenase): NADH to CoQ; pumps H+; inhibited by rotenone.','Complex II (succinate dehydrogenase): FADH2 to CoQ; does NOT pump H+; inhibited by malonate.','Complex III (cytochrome bc1): CoQ to cyt c; pumps H+; inhibited by antimycin A.','Complex IV (cytochrome c oxidase): cyt c to O2, forming H2O; pumps H+; inhibited by cyanide, CO, azide.','Complex V (ATP synthase): H+ flow back into matrix drives ATP synthesis; inhibited by oligomycin.','P:O ratios: NADH ~2.5 ATP; FADH2 ~1.5 ATP. Net per glucose: ~30-32 ATP (depends on shuttle).']},{t:'p',x:'Uncouplers (2,4-DNP, thermogenin/UCP1 in brown fat) dissipate the proton gradient as heat. ETC continues running at high rate but no ATP is made. Brown fat uses UCP1 for thermogenesis in infants and hibernators.'},{t:'p',x:'Gluconeogenesis (liver and kidney): reverse of glycolysis except at four irreversible bypass steps. Substrates: lactate (Cori cycle), glycerol, glucogenic amino acids. Even-chain fatty acids CANNOT contribute net carbon to glucose because acetyl-CoA enters TCA but is fully oxidized to CO2 with no net carbon gain.'},{t:'list',x:['1. Pyruvate carboxylase (mitochondria): pyruvate + CO2 → OAA; needs ATP and biotin (B7); activated by acetyl-CoA.','2. PEPCK (cytosol): OAA → PEP; uses GTP.','3. Fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase: F-1,6-BP → F-6-P; rate-limiting step; inhibited by AMP and F-2,6-BP.','4. Glucose-6-phosphatase (ER, liver only): G-6-P → glucose. Muscle lacks this enzyme and cannot export glucose.']},{t:'p',x:'Glycogen metabolism: Glycogen synthase (alpha-1,4 bonds; branching enzyme adds alpha-1,6 branch points). Glycogen phosphorylase (rate-limiting for glycogenolysis) cleaves alpha-1,4 bonds to release G-1-P. Insulin activates glycogen synthase (via dephosphorylation) and suppresses phosphorylase. Glucagon and epinephrine activate cAMP → PKA, which phosphorylates both enzymes (activates phosphorylase, inactivates synthase).'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Glycogen storage disease high-yield list: Type I (von Gierke): G-6-Pase deficiency, severe fasting hypoglycemia, hepatomegaly. Type II (Pompe): lysosomal alpha-1,4-glucosidase deficiency, cardiomegaly, hypotonia (ONLY glycogen storage disease affecting the heart). Type III (Cori): debranching enzyme deficiency, milder hypoglycemia, normal lactate. Type V (McArdle): muscle glycogen phosphorylase deficiency, exercise intolerance, NO lactate rise with exercise.'},{t:'p',x:'Pentose phosphate pathway (HMP shunt): cytoplasm. Makes NADPH (rate-limiting step: G6PD) and ribose-5-phosphate for nucleotide synthesis. NADPH supports reductive biosynthesis (FA and cholesterol synthesis), glutathione regeneration (antioxidant defense), and the respiratory burst in phagocytes. G6PD deficiency causes hemolytic anemia with oxidative stress (fava beans, sulfa drugs, primaquine); smear shows Heinz bodies and bite cells.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient is given 2,4-dinitrophenol (DNP). Which of the following best describes the expected effect on mitochondrial respiration?',choices:['A) Electron flow stops and O2 consumption falls','B) Electron flow continues and O2 consumption remains high, but ATP synthesis is uncoupled','C) The proton gradient builds until the ETC stalls and both O2 consumption and ATP synthesis fall','D) Only Complex I is inhibited; FADH2-linked reactions proceed normally'],answer:1,why:'DNP is an uncoupler: it dissipates the proton gradient by shuttling H+ across the inner mitochondrial membrane without passing through ATP synthase. Electron flow continues (O2 consumption stays high) but no ATP is made -- all energy is released as heat. Option A describes an ETC inhibitor; option C describes an ATP synthase inhibitor (oligomycin).'},{stem:'Which glycogen storage disease is the only one that causes cardiomegaly?',choices:['A) Type I (von Gierke)','B) Type II (Pompe)','C) Type III (Cori)','D) Type V (McArdle)'],answer:1,why:'Pompe disease (Type II) is caused by lysosomal alpha-1,4-glucosidase (acid maltase) deficiency. Glycogen accumulates in lysosomes throughout the body, including cardiac muscle, causing cardiomegaly and hypotonia. It is the only glycogen storage disease that prominently affects the heart.'}]},{id:'6.4',num:'6.4',title:'6.4 Lipid Metabolism and Nitrogen Metabolism',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Beta-oxidation of fatty acids occurs in the mitochondrial matrix. Fatty acids are first activated to acyl-CoA in the cytoplasm (costs 2 ATP equivalents), then transported into the mitochondria via the carnitine shuttle. Each round of beta-oxidation: 1 acetyl-CoA + 1 NADH + 1 FADH2; chain shortened by 2 carbons.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'CPT-I (carnitine palmitoyltransferase I) on the outer mitochondrial membrane is the rate-limiting step of beta-oxidation. It is inhibited by malonyl-CoA -- the first product of fatty acid SYNTHESIS. This reciprocal regulation prevents futile cycling: when the cell is making FA, it blocks their simultaneous degradation.'},{t:'list',x:['Odd-chain fatty acids: yield propionyl-CoA at the last round → methylmalonyl-CoA (requires biotin B7) → succinyl-CoA (requires B12). Succinyl-CoA enters TCA.','Unsaturated fatty acids: require extra isomerase and reductase steps; yield slightly less ATP per carbon.','Very long chain and branched fatty acids: degraded in peroxisomes (not mitochondria).']},{t:'p',x:'Fatty acid synthesis occurs in the cytoplasm. Rate-limiting enzyme: acetyl-CoA carboxylase (ACC), which makes malonyl-CoA from acetyl-CoA + CO2 using biotin. ACC is activated by citrate and insulin; inhibited by palmitoyl-CoA (end product) and glucagon. FA synthase (multi-domain) extends the chain by 2C per cycle using malonyl-CoA and NADPH, producing palmitate (C16). Acetyl-CoA exits the mitochondria via the citrate shuttle.'},{t:'p',x:'Ketone bodies: made in the liver from acetyl-CoA during fasting, starvation, and DKA. Products: acetoacetate, beta-hydroxybutyrate, acetone. Rate-limiting: HMG-CoA synthase (mitochondrial; distinct from the cytosolic HMG-CoA reductase that makes cholesterol). The liver cannot use ketones (lacks thiophorase/succinyl-CoA transferase); brain and muscle oxidize them for energy.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'DKA (Type 1 diabetes): no insulin → unrestrained lipolysis → FFA flood to liver → beta-oxidation overwhelms TCA capacity → acetyl-CoA accumulates → ketogenesis → metabolic acidosis with high anion gap. Hyperglycemia causes osmotic diuresis and dehydration. Kussmaul respiration is respiratory compensation. Treatment: insulin + IV fluids + K+ replacement (insulin shifts K+ into cells, so give K+ before or with insulin).'},{t:'p',x:'Cholesterol synthesis: cytoplasm and ER. Rate-limiting: HMG-CoA reductase (target of statins). Cholesterol is a precursor to bile acids, steroid hormones, vitamin D, and a structural membrane component.'},{t:'list',x:['Chylomicron: dietary TG, made in intestine, largest/lowest density lipoprotein.','VLDL: endogenous TG, made in liver; becomes IDL then LDL.','LDL: delivers cholesterol to peripheral tissues ("bad" cholesterol).','HDL: reverse cholesterol transport from tissues back to liver ("good" cholesterol).']},{t:'p',x:'Amino acid catabolism begins with transamination: AA + alpha-KG → alpha-keto acid + glutamate. ALT uses alanine; AST uses aspartate. Both require PLP (B6). Glutamate dehydrogenase then performs oxidative deamination: glutamate → alpha-KG + NH3 + NADH.'},{t:'p',x:'NH3 is toxic (especially to the brain). It is converted to urea in the liver by the urea cycle, which is partly mitochondrial and partly cytosolic.'},{t:'list',x:['1. CPS-I (mitochondria): NH3 + CO2 → carbamoyl phosphate; rate-limiting; activated by N-acetylglutamate (signals AA surplus); uses 2 ATP.','2. OTC (mitochondria): carbamoyl-P + ornithine → citrulline. OTC deficiency is X-linked, the most common urea cycle defect.','3. Argininosuccinate synthase (cytosol): citrulline + aspartate → argininosuccinate.','4. Argininosuccinase: argininosuccinate → arginine + fumarate.','5. Arginase: arginine → urea + ornithine (ornithine recycled).','Net: 2 nitrogen atoms (one from NH3, one from aspartate) + CO2 + 3 ATP → 1 urea molecule.']},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'KETOGENIC vs GLUCOGENIC amino acids. Ketogenic ONLY (Leu, Lys): produce only acetyl-CoA or acetoacetyl-CoA -- cannot net produce glucose because acetyl-CoA is fully oxidized in TCA with no net carbon gain for gluconeogenesis. Glucogenic: produce pyruvate or TCA intermediates (other than acetyl-CoA) which CAN enter gluconeogenesis. BOTH glucogenic and ketogenic: Phe, Tyr, Trp, Ile, Thr.'},{t:'p',x:'Nucleotide metabolism: De novo purine synthesis builds the ring ON the ribose sugar from PRPP, using glycine, aspartate, glutamine, CO2, and formyl-THF. Rate-limiting: glutamine PRPP amidotransferase, inhibited by IMP, AMP, GMP. De novo pyrimidine synthesis builds the ring first (from aspartate, glutamine, CO2) then attaches to PRPP; rate-limiting: CPS-II (cytoplasmic, different from urea cycle CPS-I). Salvage pathway: HGPRT recycles purines; APRT recycles adenine. Lesch-Nyhan syndrome: HGPRT deficiency → no purine salvage → de novo overdrive → uric acid overproduction → gout + self-mutilation + intellectual disability.'},{t:'list',x:['Purine degradation → uric acid (via xanthine oxidase); gout treated with allopurinol (xanthine oxidase inhibitor).','Methotrexate: inhibits dihydrofolate reductase → decreased THF → decreased thymidylate synthesis.','5-FU: inhibits thymidylate synthase directly.','6-MP: inhibits purine synthesis; must first be activated by HGPRT (so Lesch-Nyhan patients cannot activate 6-MP).','Hydroxyurea: inhibits ribonucleotide reductase (blocks dNTP synthesis).']}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient with an X-linked disorder has elevated uric acid, gout, and self-mutilating behavior. Which enzyme is deficient?',choices:['A) Adenine phosphoribosyltransferase (APRT)','B) Hypoxanthine-guanine phosphoribosyltransferase (HGPRT)','C) Glutamine PRPP amidotransferase','D) Xanthine oxidase'],answer:1,why:'Lesch-Nyhan syndrome is caused by HGPRT deficiency (X-linked). Loss of purine salvage drives de novo synthesis into overdrive, producing excess uric acid (gout). The neuropsychiatric features (self-mutilation, intellectual disability, choreoathetosis) are hallmarks. APRT deficiency causes a different disorder without the neurologic features; xanthine oxidase excess would also raise uric acid but is not X-linked.'},{stem:'Which two amino acids are strictly ketogenic (cannot contribute net carbon to gluconeogenesis)?',choices:['A) Phenylalanine and Tyrosine','B) Leucine and Lysine','C) Isoleucine and Threonine','D) Tryptophan and Leucine'],answer:1,why:'Leucine and Lysine are the only strictly ketogenic amino acids -- they produce only acetyl-CoA or acetoacetyl-CoA, which cannot net produce glucose. Phe, Tyr, Trp, Ile, and Thr are BOTH glucogenic and ketogenic. All other amino acids are glucogenic only.'}]},{id:'6.5',num:'6.5',title:'6.5 DNA, RNA, and Molecular Biology',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'DNA replication is semiconservative and bidirectional from origins. Key enzymes in prokaryotes (and eukaryotic equivalents):'},{t:'list',x:['Helicase: unwinds the double helix at the replication fork.','Topoisomerase: relieves supercoiling ahead of the fork (target of fluoroquinolones in bacteria: DNA gyrase / topoisomerase II).','SSB proteins: stabilize single-stranded DNA template.','Primase: makes short RNA primer -- DNA polymerase cannot start de novo.','DNA Pol III (prokaryotes) / Pol delta and epsilon (eukaryotes): main replicative polymerase; extends from primer.','DNA Pol I (prokaryotes): removes RNA primer and replaces with DNA.','Ligase: seals Okazaki fragment nicks on the lagging strand.','Proofreading: DNA polymerase 3\' → 5\' exonuclease activity (reads backward to excise mismatches).']},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Telomerase uses its own RNA template to extend the 3\' end of chromosomes with TTAGGG repeats, preventing shortening. Active in stem cells, germ cells, and most cancer cells (enables replicative immortality).'},{t:'p',x:'Transcription: RNA polymerase does NOT need a primer. In eukaryotes, RNA Pol II makes mRNA. Eukaryotic mRNA processing: 5\' 7-methylguanosine cap (added co-transcriptionally; required for ribosome binding and mRNA stability), splicing of introns by snRNPs (spliceosome), and 3\' poly-A tail (added post-transcriptionally; aids stability and export).'},{t:'p',x:'Translation: ribosomes are two subunits. Eukaryotic: 80S = 60S (large) + 40S (small). Prokaryotic: 70S = 50S + 30S. Stages: initiation (ribosome assembles at start codon), elongation (A site receives aminoacyl-tRNA; peptide bond formed; P site holds growing chain; E site ejects empty tRNA; ribosome translocates), termination (release factor recognizes stop codon; chain released).'},{t:'p',x:'Antibiotic targets -- antibiotics that target the ribosome selectively kill bacteria because the prokaryotic 70S ribosome differs from the eukaryotic 80S:'},{t:'list',x:['Aminoglycosides (gentamicin, streptomycin): 30S subunit; cause misreading of mRNA.','Tetracyclines: 30S subunit; block the A site (prevent aminoacyl-tRNA from binding).','Macrolides (erythromycin, azithromycin): 50S subunit; block translocation.','Chloramphenicol: 50S subunit; inhibits peptidyl transferase.','Linezolid: 50S subunit; blocks initiation.','Rifampin: bacterial RNA polymerase (inhibits transcription).','Fluoroquinolones (ciprofloxacin): DNA gyrase (topoisomerase II) in bacteria.','Beta-lactams (penicillin, cephalosporins): transpeptidase (cell wall cross-linking).','Vancomycin: D-Ala-D-Ala terminus of peptidoglycan precursor (cell wall synthesis).']},{t:'p',x:'DNA repair pathways: nucleotide excision repair removes bulky lesions (pyrimidine dimers from UV). Base excision repair removes small damaged bases. Mismatch repair corrects replication errors. Double-strand breaks are repaired by homologous recombination (error-free, uses sister chromatid) or non-homologous end joining (error-prone). BRCA1/2 mutations impair homologous recombination.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A bacterium is treated with an antibiotic that prevents aminoacyl-tRNA from entering the A site. Which antibiotic class is responsible?',choices:['A) Aminoglycosides','B) Macrolides','C) Tetracyclines','D) Chloramphenicol'],answer:2,why:'Tetracyclines block the A site on the 30S subunit, preventing aminoacyl-tRNA from binding. Aminoglycosides bind the 30S but cause misreading. Macrolides block translocation at the 50S. Chloramphenicol inhibits peptidyl transferase at the 50S.'}]},{id:'6.6',num:'6.6',title:'6.6 Vitamins, Cofactors, and Hormonal Integration',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Vitamins are divided into fat-soluble (A, D, E, K) and water-soluble (B complex, C). Fat-soluble vitamins are stored in fat and liver; excess causes toxicity. Water-soluble vitamins are generally excreted in urine; B12 is the exception (stored in liver for years).'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'B12 and folate BOTH cause megaloblastic anemia (impaired DNA synthesis in dividing cells → large, immature RBCs). ONLY B12 deficiency causes neurologic disease (subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord) due to failure of methylmalonyl-CoA mutase and methionine synthase. B12 requires intrinsic factor from gastric parietal cells for absorption in the terminal ileum; pernicious anemia is autoimmune destruction of parietal cells.'},{t:'list',x:['B1 (thiamine) / TPP: cofactor for PDH, alpha-KG dehydrogenase, transketolase (PPP), branched-chain AA DH. Deficiency: beriberi (wet = heart failure, dry = peripheral neuropathy), Wernicke-Korsakoff (ataxia, ophthalmoplegia, confusion; in alcoholics).','B2 (riboflavin) / FAD, FMN: redox reactions. Deficiency: cheilosis (cracked lip corners), glossitis.','B3 (niacin) / NAD+, NADP+: redox; synthesized from tryptophan (requires B2, B6). Deficiency: pellagra (3 Ds: dermatitis, diarrhea, dementia). Excess niacin (pharmacologic): flushing, used to raise HDL.','B5 (pantothenate) / CoA: acyl group carrier. Deficiency rare.','B6 (pyridoxine) / PLP: transamination, decarboxylation, glycogen phosphorylase. Deficiency: sideroblastic anemia, peripheral neuropathy, convulsions (especially in isoniazid-treated patients).','B7 (biotin): carboxylation reactions (pyruvate carboxylase, ACC, propionyl-CoA carboxylase). Deficiency rare; raw egg white (avidin) binds and inactivates biotin.','B9 (folate) / THF: 1-carbon transfers, thymidylate synthesis (via thymidylate synthase), purine synthesis. Deficiency: megaloblastic anemia, neural tube defects (periconceptional supplementation critical).','B12 (cobalamin) / methylcobalamin, adenosylcobalamin: methylmalonyl-CoA mutase (odd-chain FA and branched-chain AA catabolism) and methionine synthase (remethylation of homocysteine). Deficiency: megaloblastic anemia + subacute combined degeneration (posterior and lateral columns).','Vitamin C (ascorbate): hydroxylation of proline/lysine in collagen synthesis, iron absorption (reduces Fe3+ → Fe2+), antioxidant. Deficiency: scurvy (perifollicular hemorrhages, poor wound healing, bleeding gums).','Vitamin A (retinol): vision (retinal is chromophore in rhodopsin), gene expression (retinoic acid activates nuclear receptors), epithelial differentiation. Deficiency: night blindness, dry skin (xerophthalmia). Excess (teratogenic): birth defects.','Vitamin D (cholecalciferol): hydroxylated in liver (25-OH) then kidney (1,25-OH = calcitriol = active form). Promotes Ca2+ and phosphate absorption. Deficiency: rickets (children, bowed legs), osteomalacia (adults, soft bones).','Vitamin E (tocopherol): antioxidant (protects polyunsaturated FA in membranes from oxidation). Deficiency: hemolytic anemia, neurologic dysfunction.','Vitamin K (phylloquinone): gamma-carboxylation of glutamate residues in clotting factors II, VII, IX, X, and proteins C, S, Z. Deficiency or warfarin: prolonged PT/INR, bleeding.']},{t:'p',x:'Hormonal integration of metabolism across metabolic states:'},{t:'list',x:['Fed state (insulin dominant): glycogenesis, lipogenesis, protein synthesis. Glucose uptake into muscle and fat via GLUT4 (insulin-dependent). Glucokinase induced in liver.','Early fasting (glucagon dominant, ~12 hours): glycogenolysis supplies glucose. Gluconeogenesis begins.','Prolonged fasting (glucagon + cortisol, 1-3 days): gluconeogenesis dominates; protein breakdown provides glucogenic AA.','Starvation (>3 days, cortisol + glucagon + low T3): ketone bodies become the primary brain fuel; protein catabolism slows (conservation mode).']},{t:'p',x:'Insulin secretion mechanism: glucose enters beta cell → glucokinase → glycolysis → ATP rises → ATP-sensitive K+ channel closes → membrane depolarizes → voltage-gated Ca2+ channel opens → Ca2+ influx → insulin exocytosis. Sulfonylureas (glibenclamide) close the K-ATP channel directly, stimulating insulin release independently of glucose.'},{t:'list',x:['Glucagon (alpha cells): secreted in response to low blood glucose and high amino acids; stimulates glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis.','Cortisol: stress hormone; promotes gluconeogenesis, protein catabolism, lipolysis, and immunosuppression.','Epinephrine: acute stress; stimulates glycogenolysis and lipolysis via beta-adrenergic receptors and cAMP.','Type 1 diabetes: autoimmune destruction of beta cells; absolute insulin deficiency; ketosis-prone.','Type 2 diabetes: insulin resistance (decreased receptor sensitivity); eventual beta cell exhaustion; not usually ketotic.','DKA: Type 1 diabetics; high glucose + high ketones (beta-hydroxybutyrate > acetoacetate) + high anion gap metabolic acidosis + Kussmaul breathing.','HHS (Hyperosmolar Hyperglycemic State): Type 2 diabetics; very high glucose, NO significant ketosis, severe dehydration/hyperosmolarity.']}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient with terminal ileum resection develops fatigue, glossy tongue, and difficulty walking. Peripheral blood smear shows hypersegmented neutrophils and macro-ovalocytes. Which deficiency best explains the NEUROLOGIC findings?',choices:['A) Folate deficiency','B) Vitamin B12 deficiency','C) Vitamin B6 deficiency','D) Vitamin B1 deficiency'],answer:1,why:'B12 absorption requires intrinsic factor and occurs exclusively in the terminal ileum. Terminal ileum resection causes B12 deficiency, producing megaloblastic anemia (hypersegmented neutrophils, macro-ovalocytes) PLUS subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord (posterior column loss: proprioception/vibration; lateral column loss: spasticity). Folate deficiency causes identical hematologic findings but does NOT cause neurologic disease. B6 and B1 deficiencies cause different neurologic patterns and do not produce megaloblastic anemia.'},{stem:'A fed patient has elevated insulin. Which of the following metabolic effects is MOST directly driven by this insulin elevation?',choices:['A) Activation of hormone-sensitive lipase in adipose tissue','B) Stimulation of gluconeogenesis in the liver','C) Translocation of GLUT4 to the plasma membrane of muscle and fat cells','D) Activation of glycogen phosphorylase via PKA'],answer:2,why:'Insulin stimulates GLUT4 translocation to the cell surface in muscle and adipose tissue, enabling glucose uptake -- the defining anabolic signal of the fed state. Hormone-sensitive lipase and glycogen phosphorylase are activated by glucagon/epinephrine (catabolic state). Gluconeogenesis is suppressed by insulin.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Biochemistry is metabolic logic: electrons flow to oxygen, regulation is always allosteric.',
 nextHint:'Part VIII is the master discriminator index: use it as a final-week diagnostic.',
},
{
 n:7,
 title:'Master Discriminator Index',
 subtitle:'Part VIII of IX',
 tag:'Discriminators',
 foundational:'discriminator pairs, high-frequency MCAT traps, cross-subject distinctions',
 buildsOn:'Parts II-VII (all subject reviews)',
 setsUp:'Part IX (Test-Day Anchors)',
 objectives:['Identify the exact distinction between the most common MCAT trap pairs','Use this index as a final-week diagnostic: any pair that does not retrieve in five seconds needs work','Connect each discriminator to the parent chapter in Books 1-6 for mechanism review if needed'],
 opener:'The discriminator index exists for one reason: most wrong answers on the MCAT come from confusing two things that are almost alike. This part catalogs the high-frequency pairs by subject. Read it as flashcards, not prose.',
 pinnedDisc:{label:'HOW TO USE',x:'Cover the right side of each discriminator. Read the left side. Retrieve the distinction. Any pair that takes more than five seconds to retrieve is a weak spot. Return to the parent chapter in Books 1-6.'},
 sections:[{id:'7.1',num:'7.1',title:'7.1 Biology Discriminators',blocks:[{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Mitosis vs Meiosis I: mitosis separates sister chromatids; meiosis I separates homologs (reductional division).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Meiosis I vs Meiosis II: meiosis I halves chromosome number; meiosis II separates sister chromatids on already-haploid cells.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Prokaryote vs Eukaryote: eukaryote has membrane-bound nucleus and organelles; prokaryote has neither.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Rough ER vs Smooth ER: rough ER has ribosomes and handles secreted or membrane proteins; smooth ER makes lipids and detoxifies.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Mitochondrion vs Chloroplast: both are endosymbiont-derived; chloroplast runs photosynthesis and is found in plants only.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Active vs Passive transport: active uses ATP or an established gradient; passive goes down the concentration gradient with no ATP.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Primary vs Secondary active transport: primary uses ATP directly; secondary uses an ion gradient established by primary active transport.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'MHC I vs MHC II: MHC I is on all nucleated cells and presents endogenous peptides; MHC II is on antigen-presenting cells only and presents exogenous peptides.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Helper T (CD4) vs Cytotoxic T (CD8): CD4 binds MHC II and coordinates immune response; CD8 binds MHC I and directly kills infected cells.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Innate vs Adaptive immunity: innate is fast, non-specific, no memory, pattern-based; adaptive is slower initially, specific, and generates memory.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'IgG vs IgM: IgG dominates the secondary response and crosses the placenta; IgM dominates the primary response and is a pentamer.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Gram positive vs Gram negative: gram-positive has thick peptidoglycan that retains crystal violet; gram-negative has an outer membrane with LPS and loses crystal violet.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Sympathetic vs Parasympathetic: sympathetic releases NE, drives fight-or-flight; parasympathetic releases ACh, drives rest-and-digest.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Rods vs Cones: rods function in low light, no color, peripheral vision; cones detect color, concentrated at fovea, central vision.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Right shift vs Left shift (Hb-O2 curve): right shift (Bohr effect) releases O2 at tissues; left shift holds O2 more tightly (fetal Hb, CO poisoning).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Loop of Henle descending vs ascending: descending limb is permeable to water only; ascending limb is permeable to solute only, not water.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Aldosterone vs ADH: aldosterone drives Na+ reabsorption (water follows) and K+ excretion; ADH drives water reabsorption via aquaporin insertion.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Insulin vs Glucagon: insulin is the fed/anabolic hormone; glucagon is the fasting/catabolic hormone.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Endotoxin vs Exotoxin: endotoxin is LPS in the gram-negative outer membrane, heat stable; exotoxin is a secreted protein, often heat-labile.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Leading vs Lagging strand: leading strand is synthesized continuously 5 to 3 toward the replication fork; lagging strand is made as discontinuous Okazaki fragments.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Replication vs Transcription: replication copies DNA to DNA (entire genome); transcription copies DNA to RNA (one gene at a time).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Operon vs Eukaryotic gene regulation: operons are polycistronic with one switch; eukaryotic genes are monocistronic with multilayer regulation.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'DNA vs RNA: DNA uses deoxyribose, thymine, and is double-stranded; RNA uses ribose, uracil, and is single-stranded.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A cell is producing antibodies for the first time in response to a new antigen. Which antibody class dominates this primary response?',choices:['A) IgG','B) IgM','C) IgA','D) IgE'],answer:1,why:'IgM is the pentameric antibody that dominates the primary immune response. IgG dominates the secondary response and also crosses the placenta.'},{stem:'Which of the following best distinguishes MHC class I from MHC class II presentation?',choices:['A) MHC I is found only on B cells; MHC II is found on all cells','B) MHC I presents exogenous peptides; MHC II presents endogenous peptides','C) MHC I is found on all nucleated cells and presents endogenous peptides; MHC II is found on APCs and presents exogenous peptides','D) MHC I activates CD4+ T cells; MHC II activates CD8+ T cells'],answer:2,why:'MHC I is expressed on all nucleated cells and presents endogenous (cytoplasmic) peptides to CD8+ cytotoxic T cells. MHC II is restricted to APCs and presents exogenous antigens to CD4+ helper T cells.'}]},{id:'7.2',num:'7.2',title:'7.2 General Chemistry Discriminators',blocks:[{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Ionic vs Covalent vs Metallic bond: ionic forms when electronegativity difference is greater than 1.7; covalent forms when difference is less than 1.7; metallic bond is an electron sea between metal atoms.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'H-bond vs Dipole-dipole: H-bonds require N-H, O-H, or F-H donors interacting with N, O, or F acceptors; H-bond is a specific subset of dipole-dipole interaction.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Endothermic vs Exothermic: endothermic absorbs heat, delta H greater than 0; exothermic releases heat, delta H less than 0.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Spontaneous vs Nonspontaneous: spontaneous reactions have delta G less than 0; at equilibrium delta G equals 0.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Galvanic vs Electrolytic cell: galvanic is spontaneous with positive cell potential; electrolytic is non-spontaneous and requires external voltage (negative cell potential).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Strong vs Weak acid: strong acid fully dissociates (large Ka); weak acid partially dissociates and has meaningful buffering capacity.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Buffer region vs Equivalence point: the buffer region is near the pKa where pH resists change; at the equivalence point moles of acid equal moles of base.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Le Chatelier shift direction: adding a reactant shifts equilibrium forward; increasing temperature shifts toward the endothermic direction.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A reaction has delta H less than 0 and delta S less than 0. Under which condition is it spontaneous?',choices:['A) Always spontaneous','B) Never spontaneous','C) Spontaneous at low temperatures','D) Spontaneous at high temperatures'],answer:2,why:'Delta G = delta H minus T times delta S. When both delta H and delta S are negative, delta G is negative (spontaneous) at low temperatures where the negative delta H term dominates.'},{stem:'In an electrolytic cell, what is true about the cell potential?',choices:['A) E cell is positive and the reaction is spontaneous','B) E cell is negative and external voltage must be applied','C) E cell is zero at equilibrium','D) E cell is positive but no current flows'],answer:1,why:'Electrolytic cells run non-spontaneous reactions (negative cell potential) by applying an external voltage. This contrasts with galvanic cells, which are spontaneous with positive cell potential.'}]},{id:'7.3',num:'7.3',title:'7.3 Organic Chemistry Discriminators',blocks:[{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'SN1 vs SN2: SN1 requires tertiary substrate, polar protic solvent, produces racemization, proceeds through a carbocation intermediate; SN2 requires primary substrate, polar aprotic solvent, produces inversion, proceeds in a concerted one-step mechanism.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'E1 vs E2: E1 mirrors SN1 conditions (carbocation intermediate, weak base, polar protic); E2 requires a strong base and anti-periplanar geometry, proceeds in a concerted single step.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Ortho/para vs Meta directors: electron-donating groups activate the ring and direct ortho/para; electron-withdrawing groups deactivate the ring and direct meta; halogens are the exception (deactivating but ortho/para directing).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Aldehyde vs Ketone: aldehyde has the carbonyl at the end of a chain (CHO), is more reactive, and can be oxidized to a carboxylic acid; ketone has the carbonyl between two carbons and cannot be oxidized easily.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Carboxylic acid vs Ester: carboxylic acid has a free OH that acts as an H-bond donor and is acidic; ester has no H on oxygen, smells fruity, and hydrolyzes to a carboxylic acid plus an alcohol.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Reducing vs Non-reducing sugar: a reducing sugar has a free anomeric carbon (available as open-chain aldehyde or ketone) and can donate electrons; sucrose is the classic non-reducing sugar because both anomeric carbons are locked in the glycosidic bond.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Alpha vs Beta glucose: alpha-glucose has the anomeric OH pointing down in Haworth projection, forming starch and glycogen; beta-glucose has anomeric OH pointing up, forming cellulose.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Enantiomers vs Diastereomers: enantiomers are non-superimposable mirror images with ALL stereocenters inverted; diastereomers have some but not all stereocenters differing (includes meso compounds and cis/trans isomers).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Alpha helix vs Beta sheet: in an alpha helix, H-bonds form between residue i and residue i+4 within a single strand; in a beta sheet, H-bonds form between separate adjacent strands.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Which set of conditions best favors an SN2 reaction?',choices:['A) Tertiary substrate, polar protic solvent, weak nucleophile','B) Primary substrate, polar aprotic solvent, strong nucleophile','C) Tertiary substrate, polar aprotic solvent, strong nucleophile','D) Secondary substrate, polar protic solvent, weak base'],answer:1,why:'SN2 proceeds best with a primary (unhindered) substrate, a strong nucleophile, and a polar aprotic solvent. Polar aprotic solvents do not hydrogen-bond to the nucleophile, keeping it reactive.'},{stem:'A carbohydrate reduces Fehling\'s solution. This indicates the sugar has a free:',choices:['A) Hydroxyl group at C-6','B) Anomeric carbon in open-chain form','C) Glycosidic linkage at both anomeric carbons','D) Beta configuration at C-1'],answer:1,why:'A reducing sugar has a free anomeric carbon that can exist in the open-chain aldehyde or ketone form, acting as a reducing agent. Sucrose is non-reducing because both anomeric carbons are locked in the glycosidic bond.'}]},{id:'7.4',num:'7.4',title:'7.4 Physics Discriminators',blocks:[{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Elastic vs Inelastic collision: elastic collision conserves both kinetic energy and momentum; inelastic collision conserves only momentum, with kinetic energy lost as heat or deformation.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Series vs Parallel resistors: in series, equivalent resistance equals the sum of all resistors and current is the same through each; in parallel, reciprocal of equivalent resistance equals the sum of reciprocals and voltage is the same across each.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Converging vs Diverging lens: converging lens has positive focal length and can produce real or virtual images depending on object position; diverging lens has negative focal length and always produces a virtual, upright, smaller image.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Reflection vs Refraction: reflection is the bouncing of light off a surface where the angle of incidence equals the angle of reflection; refraction is the bending of light as it passes through a boundary (governed by Snell\'s law).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Doppler approach vs recede: a source approaching an observer produces a higher observed frequency; a source moving away produces a lower observed frequency.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Photon intensity vs frequency: intensity measures the number of photons (related to amplitude, brightness); frequency determines the energy per photon (E = hf).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Two resistors of 4 ohms each are connected in parallel. What is the equivalent resistance?',choices:['A) 8 ohms','B) 4 ohms','C) 2 ohms','D) 1 ohm'],answer:2,why:'For parallel resistors: 1/R_eq = 1/4 + 1/4 = 2/4 = 1/2, so R_eq = 2 ohms. In parallel, equivalent resistance is always less than any individual resistor.'},{stem:'A photoelectric effect experiment uses light of constant intensity but increasing frequency. What happens to the kinetic energy of emitted electrons?',choices:['A) Stays constant because intensity is constant','B) Decreases because fewer photons are emitted','C) Increases because each photon carries more energy','D) Stays constant because the number of electrons emitted stays the same'],answer:2,why:'Kinetic energy of emitted electrons equals hf minus the work function. Increasing frequency increases the energy per photon, raising the kinetic energy of emitted electrons. Intensity controls the number of photons (current), not energy per photon.'}]},{id:'7.5',num:'7.5',title:'7.5 Psychology and Sociology Discriminators',blocks:[{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Classical vs Operant conditioning: classical conditioning pairs stimuli to produce a reflexive response; operant conditioning pairs a voluntary behavior with a consequence to change its frequency.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Positive vs Negative reinforcement: both increase behavior; positive reinforcement adds a desirable stimulus; negative reinforcement removes an aversive stimulus.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Reinforcement vs Punishment: reinforcement (positive or negative) increases a behavior; punishment (positive or negative) decreases a behavior.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Encoding failure vs Retrieval failure: encoding failure means the memory was never stored; retrieval failure means it is stored but cannot be accessed (tip-of-the-tongue is a classic example).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'James-Lange vs Cannon-Bard theory of emotion: James-Lange holds that physiological response comes first and then the emotion is felt; Cannon-Bard holds that physiological response and emotional feeling occur simultaneously.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Schachter-Singer two-factor theory: emotion requires both physiological arousal AND a cognitive label identifying the cause of that arousal; the same arousal can produce different emotions depending on the label.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Proactive vs Retroactive interference: proactive interference is when old memories block the formation or recall of new ones; retroactive interference is when new learning disrupts recall of old memories.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Fundamental attribution error vs Self-serving bias: fundamental attribution error overattributes others\' behavior to dispositional factors; self-serving bias attributes one\'s own successes to disposition and failures to situational factors.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Functionalism vs Conflict theory: functionalism views society as cooperating parts that maintain stability; conflict theory views society as groups competing over limited resources.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Symbolic interactionism: a micro-level sociological perspective that focuses on meanings individuals derive from social interaction and symbols.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Ascribed vs Achieved status: ascribed status is assigned at birth and not chosen (race, sex assigned at birth); achieved status is earned through effort (profession, education).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Race vs Ethnicity: race emphasizes physical or biological characteristics and is socially constructed; ethnicity refers to shared culture, heritage, language, or religion.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Type I vs Type II error: Type I error is a false positive, rejecting a true null hypothesis; Type II error is a false negative, failing to reject a false null hypothesis.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A student studies Spanish in high school, then learns French in college. She now has trouble remembering her Spanish vocabulary. This is best explained by:',choices:['A) Proactive interference','B) Retroactive interference','C) Encoding failure','D) Repression'],answer:1,why:'Retroactive interference occurs when new learning (French) disrupts recall of previously learned material (Spanish). Proactive interference would be the opposite: old Spanish blocking new French learning.'},{stem:'A manager attributes a subordinate\'s late arrival to laziness, but attributes her own late arrival to heavy traffic. This pattern best illustrates:',choices:['A) Confirmation bias','B) Self-serving bias combined with fundamental attribution error','C) Fundamental attribution error only','D) Actor-observer bias'],answer:1,why:'The manager uses dispositional attribution for others (fundamental attribution error) and situational attribution for her own failure (self-serving bias). This is the classic combined pattern tested on the MCAT.'}]},{id:'7.6',num:'7.6',title:'7.6 Biochemistry Discriminators',blocks:[{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Hexokinase vs Glucokinase: hexokinase has a low Km (high affinity), is inhibited by its product glucose-6-phosphate, and is found in most tissues; glucokinase has a high Km (low affinity), is not inhibited by G6P, and is found in liver and pancreatic beta cells.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Glycolysis rate-limiting enzyme vs Gluconeogenesis rate-limiting enzyme: the rate-limiting step of glycolysis is phosphofructokinase-1 (PFK-1); the key bypass enzyme in gluconeogenesis is fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Glycogenesis vs Glycogenolysis: glycogenesis (glycogen synthesis) is driven by glycogen synthase and stimulated by insulin; glycogenolysis (glycogen breakdown) is driven by glycogen phosphorylase and stimulated by glucagon and epinephrine.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'ETC inhibitor vs Uncoupler: an ETC inhibitor stops electron flow and ATP synthesis; an uncoupler (such as DNP) dissipates the proton gradient as heat, so electron flow and oxygen consumption continue but no ATP is made.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'Ketogenic vs Glucogenic amino acids: purely ketogenic amino acids (leucine and lysine) cannot contribute to net glucose synthesis; glucogenic amino acids enter gluconeogenesis pathways and can produce glucose.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR',x:'De novo vs Salvage nucleotide synthesis: de novo synthesis builds nucleotides from small precursors from scratch; salvage synthesis recycles free bases using enzymes such as HGPRT and APRT.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A metabolic poison dissipates the mitochondrial proton gradient but does not directly inhibit the electron transport chain. Which of the following best describes its effect?',choices:['A) Electron flow stops and ATP synthesis stops','B) Electron flow continues, oxygen consumption increases, and ATP synthesis stops','C) Electron flow stops but ATP synthesis continues via substrate-level phosphorylation','D) ATP synthesis continues at a reduced rate'],answer:1,why:'An uncoupler (like DNP) makes the inner mitochondrial membrane leaky to protons, dissipating the gradient as heat. The ETC keeps running (and oxygen consumption actually increases) but ATP synthase cannot make ATP because there is no proton gradient to drive it.'},{stem:'Which two amino acids are purely ketogenic and cannot contribute to net glucose synthesis?',choices:['A) Leucine and Lysine','B) Phenylalanine and Tyrosine','C) Isoleucine and Threonine','D) Alanine and Glutamine'],answer:0,why:'Leucine and Lysine are the only purely ketogenic amino acids. They are converted only to acetyl-CoA or acetoacetate, which cannot produce net glucose. All other amino acids are either purely glucogenic or both glucogenic and ketogenic.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Every second of uncertainty on test day traces back to a discriminator pair that was never fully separated.',
 nextHint:'Part IX is the test-day protocol: the final ten minutes, the final ten anchors.',
},
{
 n:8,
 title:'Test-Day Anchors',
 subtitle:'Part IX of IX',
 tag:'Test Strategy',
 foundational:'test-day protocol, anchor principles, time management, stress regulation',
 buildsOn:'Part VIII (Discriminator Index)',
 setsUp:null,
 objectives:['Execute the test-day morning protocol without reviewing new material','Apply the five anchor principles when a passage or question feels unfamiliar','Use time checkpoints to avoid section-level time disasters','Distinguish between signal (retrieval failure) and noise (performance anxiety) mid-test','End each section clean: flag, move on, return'],
 opener:'Books 1 through 6 built the mechanistic scaffolding of every premedical subject. This volume compressed that scaffolding to its highest-yield form. Part IX is not a review: it is a protocol. The content is already inside you. What remains is executing the exam without interference from the exam itself.\n\nThe MCAT is a retrieval test, not a recognition test. Every question is asking whether you can generate the mechanism under time pressure, in a novel context, without confirmation from anyone else in the room. You have been building toward exactly that condition. The anchors below are the last set of reminders before you walk in.',
 pinnedDisc:{label:'ANCHOR',x:'When uncertain: mechanism first, then process of elimination. The correct answer always has a mechanistic reason.'},
 sections:[{id:'8.1',num:'8.1',title:'8.1 The Night Before and Morning Of',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The night before the exam is not a study session. It is a logistics and sleep session. Attempting new material the night before does not add points; it increases anxiety and interrupts sleep consolidation, which is when the retrieval pathways you built during the final review actually stabilize. The only review that is appropriate is a light pass over your anchor cheat sheets, the one-thing-per-topic table, and the five anchors below. That pass takes 20 minutes. After that, stop.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Night before: light review of cheat sheets only, no new material, sleep early. Morning of: eat protein plus complex carbohydrates, use caffeine only if it is already part of your routine (not a new variable), bring your ID, snacks for breaks, water for the locker, and layered clothing. Arrive early enough that logistics do not become a stressor.'},{t:'list',x:['Night before: light pass over anchor sheets only; stop at 20 minutes; no new concepts','Sleep: prioritize over any additional review; consolidation happens during sleep, not reading','Morning nutrition: protein plus complex carbohydrates; nothing that spikes and crashes blood sugar','Caffeine: only if it is already your daily routine; today is not the day to experiment','Logistics: ID (required), snacks for section breaks, water (stored in locker, not at station), layered clothing for variable room temperature','Arrive early: budget for traffic, parking, check-in; arriving rushed is avoidable']},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY IT MATTERS',x:'Sleep deprivation degrades working memory and processing speed, both of which are directly tested on the MCAT. A student who slept 8 hours and stopped reviewing at 9pm will outperform the same student who crammed until 2am, even if the late crammer reviewed material that appeared on the exam. The material is already there. The night before is about not subtracting from what you built.'},{t:'p',x:'Between sections during the exam: stand up, stretch, hydrate, eat brief carbohydrates if available. Do not review missed questions, do not open notes, do not discuss answers with others in the testing center. What is done is done. The next section begins fresh; it does not inherit the previous one.'}],quickcheck:[]},{id:'8.2',num:'8.2',title:'8.2 The Five Anchors',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'When a question or passage feels unfamiliar, the default response is to slow down, re-read, and eventually talk yourself into or out of an answer based on something other than mechanism. The five anchors replace that default with a repeatable procedure. Every time you feel stuck, the anchors are the sequence to run.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'ANCHOR',x:'Anchor 1: Mechanism first. Before looking at the answer choices, restate what is happening biologically, chemically, or physically. What is the molecule doing and why? If you cannot state the mechanism in your own words, the answer choices will confuse you. If you can state it, the correct answer becomes the one that matches it.\n\nAnchor 2: Passage support always. The correct answer to any passage-based question must be supportable by something in the passage. If your answer requires knowledge the passage did not provide, you are either synthesizing correctly or importing an assumption. Check which one.\n\nAnchor 3: Process of elimination for uncertain questions. Two choices are almost always clearly wrong. Cross them out. Then choose between the remaining two using mechanism, not vocabulary similarity. The trap answer often uses the right words in the wrong relationship.\n\nAnchor 4: Flag and move. If you cannot get traction in 30 seconds, mark the question and move to the next one. Spending 3 minutes on one question while leaving 4 questions unanswered is a worse outcome than guessing on one and getting the other four right. Time is the resource you cannot recover.\n\nAnchor 5: Breathe. If anxiety is rising mid-section, 4 counts in and 6 counts out, one cycle. Then return to the current question only. Not the section, not the exam: the current question.'},{t:'p',x:'The most common mid-exam error is mistaking performance anxiety for retrieval failure. Anxiety produces the sensation that you do not know something. Retrieval failure means the information is not there. They feel identical but require different responses. Anxiety responds to a breath and a reset. Retrieval failure responds to process of elimination and mechanism inference. When in doubt, assume anxiety first: run the breath, restate the mechanism, then decide whether the information is actually missing.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY IT MATTERS',x:'The MCAT is designed to produce a stress response in students who are unprepared for its difficulty and pacing. The test writer assumes that a student who does not know the mechanism will slow down, spiral, and lose time. The anchors are a pre-committed protocol that runs instead of the spiral. They do not guarantee the right answer; they guarantee that you use the time and information available to maximize the probability of the right answer.'},{t:'list',x:['Anchor 1: Mechanism first, restate in your own words before reading choices','Anchor 2: Passage support, every correct answer to a passage question is in the passage','Anchor 3: Process of elimination, cross out two clearly wrong choices, choose between the rest by mechanism','Anchor 4: Flag and move at 30 seconds if no traction; return at section end','Anchor 5: 4-in-6-out breath when anxiety rises, then return to the current question only']}],quickcheck:[]},{id:'8.3',num:'8.3',title:'8.3 Section-by-Section Protocol',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Each section of the MCAT has a different cognitive demand profile. Running the same pacing strategy across all four sections is a mistake. The protocol below maps the specific approach for each section.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD',x:'Sciences (C/P, B/B, P/S): approximately 1.5 minutes per question, 7 to 8 minutes per passage on average. Discretes go faster; passages slower. CARS: approximately 10 minutes per passage including all questions. Do not save CARS passages for the end of a time block. Last 5 minutes of any section: confirm every question has an answer selected. There is no penalty for guessing; a blank is always wrong.'},{t:'list',x:['C/P (59 questions, 95 min): mostly physics plus gen chem plus some biochem; passages are quantitative; estimate aggressively, watch units; target 1.5 min/question','CARS (53 questions, 90 min): no outside knowledge; main idea, author tone, inference; do not import real-world knowledge; approximately 10 min per passage including questions','B/B (59 questions, 95 min): bio plus biochem plus some orgo; experimental passages dominate; reason from mechanism; 1.5 min/question','P/S (59 questions, 95 min): terminology-heavy, mechanism-light; vocabulary recall is the main lever; 1.5 min/question','Skip and flag rule: no traction in 30 seconds, mark and move; return at section end','Discrete questions (no passage): appear in clusters; treat as pure recall; these should go faster than passage questions','Last 5 minutes: confirm every question has an answer; no blanks; no penalty for guessing']},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'ANCHOR',x:'CARS trap: bringing in outside knowledge. CARS does not reward what you know about the world; it rewards what you can derive from the passage. A student who knows the correct real-world answer to a CARS question but cannot find passage support for it must treat that knowledge as noise and answer from the passage only. The test is measuring analytical reading, not background knowledge.'},{t:'p',x:'Common trap patterns across all sections: extreme language (always, never, all, none) is almost always wrong in CARS and P/S. Choices that mix correct vocabulary with the wrong causal relationship are the most dangerous traps in science sections; read for the relationship, not just the words. Calculation choices in C/P often include the result of common unit errors at a factor of 10: always check the magnitude of your answer, not just the number. Premise-flipped questions (the stem gives an inhibitor where you expect an activator, or a loss-of-function mutation where you expect gain-of-function) require you to reverse the normal prediction: slow down when the question stem describes a modification to a system you recognize.'}],quickcheck:[]},{id:'8.4',num:'8.4',title:'8.4 After the Exam',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'When the last section ends, the exam is over. There is no productive analysis of your performance in the parking lot, in the car home, or at dinner. The questions you thought you got wrong may be questions you got right. The questions you felt confident about may have traps you did not catch. You cannot know, and speculating does not move the number. What you can control after the exam is recovery: food, sleep, and distance from the content for at least 24 hours.'},{t:'p',x:'A score is one data point about your performance on one test on one day. It reflects how well your retrieval held up under pressure and time constraints against a test designed to discriminate. It does not measure your capacity to learn medicine, your quality as a future physician, or your potential beyond the MCAT. What it measures is whether you built a mechanistic foundation and retrieved it under exam conditions. If the score reflects what you built, that is the expected outcome. If it does not, the mechanism is still there: the retrieval process is what to diagnose, not the foundation.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY IT MATTERS',x:'The C-Factor Series ends where it began: every concept earned mechanistically, retrievable in seconds, transferable to any context the exam puts in front of you. Book 7 compresses Books 1 through 6 into a final-pass reference, reduced to its highest-yield bullets, tables, and discriminators. The Master Discriminator Index in Part VIII is the single best diagnostic tool for what you still confuse. Test-day performance follows mechanism, not memorization. If anything in Parts II through VII felt unfamiliar on first read, return to the parent chapter for the full mechanistic treatment, then use this volume to lock it in.'},{t:'p',x:'This is the end of the C-Factor Series. Six parent books covering biology, general chemistry, organic chemistry, physics, psychology and sociology, and biochemistry. One review volume compressing all six. One discriminator index surfacing what to revisit. One final chapter to hold in mind on exam day. The work is done. Walk in.'}],quickcheck:[]}],
 bottomLine:'The exam tests whether you can retrieve mechanism under pressure. You already have the mechanism.',
 nextHint:null,
}
];

